# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azraq-refugee-camp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Ain al-Hilweh was established near the city of Sidon in 1948 by the International Committee of the Red Cross to accommodate refugees from Amqa, Saffuriya, Sha'ab, Taitaba, Manshieh, al-Simireh, al-Nahr, Safsaf, Hittin, al-Ras al-Ahmar, al-Tira and Tarshiha in northern Palestine.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Ain Al-Hilweh is located on land owned by landowners from Miye ou Miye, Darb Es Sim and Sidon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Because Lebanese Armed Forces are not allowed to enter the camp, Ain al-Hilweh has been called a "zone of unlaw" by the Lebanese media.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Many people wanted by the Lebanese government are believed to have taken refuge in the camp as a result of the lack of Lebanese authority.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The direct translation of Ain al-Hilweh is "sweet water spring".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] People believe that the camp was named after a natural water spring that existed in the present-day Ain al-Hilweh refugee camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In actuality, the Ain al-Hilweh spring was located at the corner of the valley between Miye ou Miye village and Darb es Seem.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The water flowed from the spring westward 500 meters towards a manmade dam.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The dam was erected at the crossroad between Mieh Mieh and present day Seyroub neighborhood in Darb es Seem.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The Palestinian camp is located between 1000 m to 1500 m to the west, away from the natural spring.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Emir Fakhr-al-Din II, (Fakhr-al-Din Ibn Mann, Fakhr-al-Din al Maani), was given the title "emir" or "prince" in Arabic because the Maan dynasty reigned over Lebanon at that time.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Lebanon was divided into several emirates (the state or jurisdiction of an emir).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] So, there was an emirate out of several called, “Emirate of Ain al-Hilweh” and had an emir.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The emirate stretched northwest from the Ain al-Hilweh spring, looped around the bottom of Mieh Mieh village along present-day Officers’ Military Club straight north to the Barghout Creek (between Mieh Mieh and Haret Saida) and west to the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] From the south, the emirate stretched straight west to the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] So the present-day Palestinian refugee camp got its name from the Emirate Ain al-Hilweh.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The camp was established in 1948 to accommodate Palestinian refugees displaced by the 1948 Palestinian expulsion and flight which occurred during the 1948 Palestine war.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The Ain al-Hilweh Palestinian camp is spread out on private properties owned by villagers from Miye ou Miye, Darb es Sim and Sidon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The size of the Ain al-Hilweh camp in the early 1990s was around 290 dunams (72 acres).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Today, the size of the camp increased by 2.35 times to 686 dunams (170 acres).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The proportion of the land of Ain al-Hilwe camp located in the above towns is as follows: Miye ou Miye (22%), Darb Es Sim (4%) and Sidon (74%).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On 20 June 1974, the Israeli Air Force (IAF) attacked the camp, killing 11 people and injuring 32, according to the Lebanese Army.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] During the Israeli invasion of Lebanon in 1982, the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) landed north of Sidon and the city was subjected to a heavy aerial bombing, causing heavy casualties among the civilian population.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Dov Yermiya was to later liken the bombardment used on the refugee camp of Ain al-Hilweh as of an intensity which recalled the quantity of bombs used in World War 2 and described the destruction as 100%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] There was prolonged fighting in Ain al-Hilweh, culminating with the Palestinian defenders making a last stand at a mosque which was thereupon blown up by the IDF.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Following the Israeli retreat from Beirut in 1985 Ain al-Hilweh was outside the Israeli security zone.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] During the War of the Camps Ain al-Hilweh received over 8,000 Palestinians fleeing Amal gunmen and the siege of Rashidieh Camp in Tyre.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Amal had little political support in Sidon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On 24 November 1986 a coalition of fighters from all of the main factions in the camp launched an offensive against Amal positions in the strategic village of Maghdouché overlooking Sidon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] After a week of fighting they gained control of most of the village.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Israeli Air Force airstrikes, 6 & 8 May 1987, on a residential area of Ain al-Hilweh killed fifteen people, wounded fifty and destroyed twenty houses.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Four months later, 6 September, another air raid on a militants headquarters in Ain al-Hilweh killed fifty-six people and wounded one hundred and ninety.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] According to UNRWA nine women were amongst the dead and twenty-one of the injured were women and children.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On 2 January 1988 night-time Israeli airstrikes on PFLP-GC positions in Ain al-Hilweh and PSP positions along the coast North of Sidon killed around twenty people, including seven children and one woman.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Three members of PFLP-GC and three from PSP were also amongst those killed.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] It was reported that the raids were retaliation for the 25 November 1987 PFLP-GC hang-glider attack in which six IDF soldiers were killed.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In the previous two years there had been about forty Israeli air strikes on Lebanon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In the 1980s, most Palestinian refugee camps in Lebanon were dominated by Syrian-backed Palestinian groups.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In the late 1980s, members of Yasser Arafat's Fatah movement, after being ousted in other refugee camps moved on to Ain al-Hilweh.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On 7 September 1990, after a three-day conflict with the Abu Nidal Organization, Fatah members were able to establish dominance in Ain al-Hilweh.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Sixty-eight people were killed in the fighting and around 300 wounded.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] It left Fatah in control of an area from the eastern suburbs of Sidon to Iqlim al-Kharrub.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On 4 July 1991, following the failure of disarmament negotiations, as required by the Taif agreement, the Lebanese Army attacked Palestinian positions in Southern Lebanon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The offensive, involving 10,000 troops against an estimated 5,000 militia, lasted 3 days and ended with the Army taking all the Palestinian positions around Sidon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In the agreement that followed all heavy weapons were surrendered and infantry weapons only allowed in the two refugee camps, Ain al-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] 73 people were killed in the fighting, and 200 wounded, mostly Palestinian.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] By 1993, another group led by Fatah's top military commander in the camp, Col.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Mounir Maqdahhad known as the Black September 13 Brigade, with support from Hezbollah and Iran, gained dominance over mainstream Fatah members in the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On 25 November 1994 fighting broke out which left ten people dead and resulted in the Fatah loyalists being expelled from the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] At the time the camp had a population of around 70,000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The following June there was a further two days of fighting between Fatah factions in which ten people were killed and about thirty wounded.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Maqdahhad's dominance was short-lived as he rejoined Fatah in 1998 after the Palestinian Authority began funding the camp again.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In 1999 a Lebanese court convicted the leader of Fatah in Lebanon, Sultan Abu al-Aynayn, of "forming an armed gang" and sentenced him in absentia to death.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In May 2003, fighting broke out between members of Osbat al-Nour and Fatah militia members in Ain al-Hilweh after the near-fatal shooting of Osbat al-Nour leader Abdullah Shraidi on 17 May, in which one of Abdullah's bodyguards and a bystander were killed.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The shooting occurred while returning from the funeral of a Fatah member and family relative, Ibrahim Shraidi who was gunned down by an unknown assailant.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Roughly 200 Osbat al-Nour fundamentalist fighters attacked Fatah offices.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Eight people were killed and 25 wounded in the fighting at Ain al-Hilweh.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Schools in Ain al-Hilweh were shut and most stores kept their shutters down at the height of the fighting, which provoked an exodus by hundreds of camp residents.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Fatah agreed to a ceasefire after failing to defeat the fundamentalists in the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Two months after the ambush Abdullah Shraidi died from wounds received during the attack.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In July 2005 four members of the Islamic Liberation Party were arrested.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The Lebanese authorities claimed that the group had connections with Syria and that the group has participated in terrorist attacks in various Arab countries.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Palestinian sources described the moves as a step toward the disarmament of their factions, in line with United Nations Security Council Resolution 1559.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On 3 June 2007, Jund al-Sham fired a rocket-propelled grenade at a Lebanese Army checkpoint near Sidon, prompting a response from the Lebanese Army leading to clashes in the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] These clashes follow a tense three weeks in Lebanon's north, where the Lebanese Army has been battling militant group Fatah al-Islam at the Palestinian refugee camp Nahr al-Bared.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In March 2008, fighting broke out between members of the Fatah faction and the Islamist group Jund al-Sham.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The conditions in the camp have been exacerbated by an influx of previously Syrian-based Palestinian refugees, as a result of the Syrian Civil War.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] As a result of this influx, the camp's population has swelled from 70,000 to as much as 120,000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] As of 2014, the camp suspected of being a popular destination for jihadist rebels fleeing neighbouring Syria, particularly after the Syrian Army, backed by the Shia Lebanese militia Hezbollah, regained control of Yabroud from the rebels in March 2014.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] In 2016 Lebanese authorities began constructing a concrete wall with watch towers around the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] The wall has faced some criticism, being called "racist" by some and supposedly labeling residents as terrorists or islamists.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] As of May 2017 the wall construction is nearly complete.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] On July 30, 2023, fighting broke out inside the camp when gunmen tried to assassinate Islamist militant Mahmoud Khalil, killing a companion of his instead.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Later, Islamist militants ambushed a Fatah military general in a parking lot, killing him and three bodyguards.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] Fighting continued the next day, with six more people being killed, bringing the death toll to eleven.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] A ceasefire was announced later in the day.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ain-al-hilweh] More than 2,000 people left the camp amid the fighting.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera is known for its in-depth and frontline reporting particularly in conflict zones such as the Arab Spring, the Gaza–Israel conflict and others.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera's coverage of the Arab Spring won the network numerous awards, including the Peabody Award.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] It positions itself as an alternative media platform to the dominance of Western media outlets like CNN and BBC, focusing on narrative reporting where subjects present their own stories.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The channel launched on 15 November 2006 with an investment of approximately $1 billion from the Qatari government.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Initially slated to be named Al Jazeera International, the channel was renamed nine months prior to the launch.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] This decision was influenced by one of the channel's backers, who argued that the original Arabic-language channel already encompassed an international scope.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The channel was expected to reach approximately 40 million households, but it significantly surpassed this launch target, reaching 80 million homes.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] By 2009, the service was accessible in every major European market and available to 130 million homes across more than 100 countries through cable and satellite, according to a network spokeswoman in Washington.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] However, the channel had limited penetration in the American market, where it was carried by only one satellite service and a handful of cable networks.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English subsequently launched a campaign to enter the North American market, including a dedicated website.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In August 2011, it became available to some cable subscribers in New York, having previously been an option for some viewers in Washington, D.C., Ohio, and Los Angeles.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The channel primarily reached the United States through its live online streaming service.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Following approval from the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission on 26 November 2009, Al Jazeera English became readily available on most major Canadian television providers, including Rogers and Bell Satellite TV.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English and Iran's state-run Press TV were the only international English-language television broadcasters with journalists reporting from inside both Gaza and Israel during the 2008–2009 Israel-Gaza conflict.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Foreign press access to Gaza was limited via either Egypt or Israel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] However, Al Jazeera's reporters Ayman Mohyeldin and Sherine Tadros were already inside Gaza when the conflict began.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The network encourages online viewing at its own website or via its channel on YouTube.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English HD launched in the United Kingdom on Freeview on 26 November 2013, and began streaming in HD on YouTube in 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 1 January 2020, Al Jazeera English debuted a new graphics package to coincide with the renovation of its main Doha studio, the last of the channel's three main studios (Doha, London, and Washington D.C.) to be upgraded since the channel's launch in 2006.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 3 January 2013, Al Jazeera Media Network announced that it had purchased Current TV in the United States and would launch an American news channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Sixty percent of the channel's programming would be produced in the United States, while 40% would be from Al Jazeera English.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] This was later changed at the request of pay-television providers to almost 100% US programming.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] However, Al Jazeera America maintained a close working relationship with Al Jazeera English.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The channel aired *Newshour* in the morning and midday hours, and cut to live Al Jazeera English coverage of large breaking international news stories outside those hours.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The Al Jazeera English programmes *Witness*, *Earthrise*, *The Listening Post*, *Talk To Al Jazeera*, *Al Jazeera Correspondent* and *101 East* along with *Al Jazeera Investigates* aired regularly on Al Jazeera America.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 13 January 2016, Al Jazeera America announced that the network would shut down on 12 April 2016, citing the "economic landscape".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In 2013, Al Jazeera Media Network began planning a new channel called *Al Jazeera UK*; the British channel was set to broadcast for five hours during prime time as a local opt-out of Al Jazeera English.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Ultimately, the planned UK channel never materialised.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English continued to broadcast some of its daily bulletins from London until July 2023, when it moved its base to Qatar.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The channel is available in many countries, mostly via satellite, sometimes via cable.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English provides a free HD stream on its website for unlimited viewing.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera news segments were frequently included on the American public television program Worldfocus which aired from 6 October 2008 until 2 April 2010.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera can also be streamed on any iOS or Android device with an internet connection using a free application.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is also available on connected TV and OTT streaming services like Pluto TV and Haystack News.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Along with a free unlimited high-quality stream on the official Al Jazeera English website, Online subscriptions allowing unlimited viewing may be purchased from Jump TV, RealPlayer, and VDC.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Headlines from Al Jazeera English are available on Twitter.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English's website also contains news reports and full episodes of their programs that can be viewed for free on their website.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The videos are hosted by YouTube, where viewers can also go to find the videos.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is available in the UK and Ireland on Freeview channel 235, Sky channel 511, Freesat channel 203 and Virgin Media channel 622.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] A notice appearing on Freeview channel 235 indicates that Al Jazeera is scheduled to end there on 30 September 2024 but that its service will remain on channel 251 as a streaming service for STBs that support streaming.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The channel initially began test streaming Al Jazeera English (then called "Al Jazeera International") in March 2006 on Hot Bird, Astra 1E, Hispasat, AsiaSat3S, Eutelsat 28A and Panamsat PAS 10.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Telenors Thor, Türksat and Eutelsat 25A were added to the satellites carrying it.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Eutelsat 28A carried the test stream on frequency 11.681 under the name "AJI".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is available in Sub-Saharan Africa mainly via DStv and StarTimes' satellite and terrestrial TV platforms.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] It is also available FTA on satellites like Belintersat 51.5°E and Nilesat 201.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In Northern Africa, Al Jazeera English is available on telcos like Etisalat.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] It is also available via satellite, on Badr°26E and various local cable operators.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In New Zealand, Al Jazeera English is available 24 hours a day on Freeview (New Zealand) channel 16 and Sky (New Zealand) channel 90.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] From October 2013, Freeview (New Zealand) broadcast on the Kordia operated free-to-air DVB-T terrestrial network.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Prior to the December 2012 analog switchoff Triangle TV re-broadcast various Al Jazeera programmes in Auckland on its free-to-air UHF channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] TV One was going to replace BBC World News with this service during their off-air hours of 01:30 to 06:00 from 1 April 2013, however opted to run infomercials instead.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In April 2010, Al Jazeera English was taken off air in Singapore Singtel TV with unspecified reasons, according to the official Al Jazeera English website.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 7 December 2010, Al Jazeera said its English language service has got a downlink license to broadcast in India.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Satellite and cable companies would therefore be allowed to broadcast Al Jazeera in the country.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The channel launched on Dish TV in November 2011, and is considering a Hindi-language channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Tata Play satellite service broadcasts this on Channel 637 (SD) in India.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 26 November 2009, the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission approved "a request to add Al Jazeera English (AJE) to the lists of eligible satellite services for distribution on a digital basis and amends the lists of eligible satellite services accordingly".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English became available on Rogers Cable, Videotron and Bell Satellite TV on 4 May 2010.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera English is available via satellite across all of North America free to air via Globecast on Galaxy 19 on the Ku band in DVB format.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] As of 2011, only a small number of Americans were able to watch the channel on their televisions.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Among the markets where it was available were Bristol County, Rhode Island, Toledo and Sandusky, Ohio, Burlington, Vermont, Houston, Texas, and Washington, DC.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Industry giant Comcast originally planned to carry Al Jazeera English in 2007, but reversed its decision shortly before the channel's launch, citing "the already-saturated television market".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The two major American satellite providers, DirecTV and Dish Network, had similar plans but also changed their minds, with speculation that the decision may have been influenced by allegations by the Bush administration of "anti-American bias" on the channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] With Al Jazeera's coverage of the Egyptian Revolution of 2011, the channel drew acclaim and received renewed attention.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] *The New York Times* reported on 1 February 2011 that 1.6 million U.S. viewers had tuned in via Internet stream, and stated that new discussions were underway with carriers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The following month, it was announced that Al Jazeera entered carriage negotiations with Comcast and Time Warner Cable.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Salon.com described the channel's English-language coverage as "mandatory viewing for anyone interested in the world-changing events currently happening in Egypt", while *Huffington Post* contributor Jeff Jarvis claimed it was "un-American" for operators to not carry the network.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] When Al Jazeera covered the Libyan Civil War, U.S.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton noted an increasing American audience for the network, saying that "viewership of Al Jazeera is going up in the United States because it's real news.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 1 February 2011, Internet appliance Roku posted on its Facebook page that the English-language Al Jazeera Live would be streaming on Roku devices through a private channel called Newscaster and also through the BBC channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] It permitted the announcement following unrest in Egypt so American viewers can watch the latest events going on in the Middle East.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] A Roku user must add the private channel Newscaster from the Roku website.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 1 August 2011, Al Jazeera English began airing 23 hours a day in New York City as part of a sublet agreement with cable channel RISE, a former Spanish-language network, which is carried on WRNN-TV's DT2 subchannel (the other hours were used to meet FCC E/I and local programming guidelines).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The network aired on Time Warner Cable on channel 92 and on Verizon FiOS on channel 481.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 2 January 2013, Al Jazeera announced that it had acquired the U.S.-based cable TV channel Current TV for a reported $500 million.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] With this acquisition, Al Jazeera launched a new channel, called Al Jazeera America, with a heavy dose of U.S. domestic news along with Al Jazeera English programming and news, to an estimated 40 million U.S. households—putting it in direct competition with CNN, MSNBC and Fox News Channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Due to contracts with U.S. cable and satellite carriers for Al Jazeera America the official Al Jazeera English live stream was geo-blocked in the United States on 18 August 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] With the launch of Al Jazeera America, Al Jazeera English was excluded from all US services carrying or providing the channel, including YouTube, with Al Jazeera America material replacing all Al Jazeera English video content and live streams.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Most Al Jazeera English video content was no longer officially available in the United States.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In April 2014 the Al Jazeera English show *Empire* was not geo-blocked in the United States.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Shortly after the programs *Indian Hospital*, *Viewfinder*, *Lifelines: The Quest for Global Health* and *Head to Head* were available also.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] These programs were the only AJE shows officially non-geoblocked for American viewing during the time that Al Jazeera America was in existence.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] With the closure of Al Jazeera America in April 2016 it was expected that the official live stream of Al Jazeera English and access to its programmes would eventually be restored to the United States.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The online live stream of Al Jazeera English was made available to viewers in the United States once again in September 2016.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Shortly after launching in 2003, Al Jazeera's English website was hit by hackers who launched denial-of-service attacks.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Aljazeera.com has served as the primary web address for both the Al Jazeera English and former Al Jazeera America websites since early 2011.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The domain name was acquired by Al Jazeera Media Network from Aljazeera Publishing, a Dubai-based media company which previously used the domain as the website for their unrelated publication Aljazeera Magazine.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] This followed after a long-running domain name dispute between the two entities, which included a failed 2005 attempt by Al Jazeera Network to take control of the domain.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Confusion between the two entities resulted in some articles from Al Jazeera magazine being erroneously attributed to the Al Jazeera Network.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In 2012, 40 percent of the 150 million visits Al Jazeera English's website received originated from the United States.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The Al Jazeera Investigative Unit is a specialized investigative journalism team within Al Jazeera.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The unit is known for producing investigative reports and documentaries on a wide range of global issues, including politics, human rights, corruption, environmental issues, and more.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The documentaries are featured as exclusive specials within their dedicated series Al Jazeera Investigates.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 29 December 2013, Egyptian security forces arrested three Al Jazeera English journalists—Australian Peter Greste, Canadian Mohamed Fahmy, and Egyptian Baher Mohamed—at Cairo's Marriott Hotel, accusing them of reporting news damaging to national security.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Despite international outcry and campaigns like #FreeAJStaff, calls for their release from the UN, EU, and the US went unheeded.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The journalists faced a series of trial delays, with questionable evidence, including misleading videos, inaudible audio recordings, and unrelated images.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 23 June 2014, Greste and Fahmy received seven-year sentences, while Mohamed was sentenced to 10 years.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The verdict was widely criticized, with global leaders and media outlets denouncing it as a politically motivated attack on press freedom.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Calls for amnesty were rebuffed by Egypt, asserting the independence of its justice system.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Amid mounting pressure, Greste was released and deported to Australia on 1 February 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 29 August 2015, the trio faced an additional three-year sentence, sparking international condemnation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The Canadian government sought Fahmy's pardon and deportation, which was granted on 23 September 2015, alongside a pardon for Mohamed, as part of a larger pardon by Egyptian President el-Sisi for 100 individuals.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The case underscored concerns about press freedom and raised calls for reevaluating foreign aid to Egypt.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] In 2012, Melissa Chan, who served as the longstanding China correspondent for Al Jazeera English, faced expulsion from the country.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Although the Chinese government refrained from publicly disclosing the reasons for her expulsion, it was widely understood that their dissatisfaction stemmed from a documentary aired by the channel that focused on China's prison system.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] The incident prompted inquiries during the Beijing press corps' routine questioning at the Chinese Foreign Ministry's daily press briefing on 8 May 2012.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] However, officials provided no explanation and selectively omitted most related questions when publishing the official transcript.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Following her expulsion, Melissa Chan continued her journalistic career at Al Jazeera America.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Emmy Award-winning journalist Dave Marash resigned from his position in March 2008, saying his exit was due in part to an anti-American bias at the network, which is little seen in the US.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Marash said he felt that attitude more from British administrators than Arabs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] He said there were other reasons for his exit and was proud of the network's coverage of issues south of the equator, but that he ultimately felt that it was not the right place for him.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 12 October 2008, Al Jazeera English broadcast interviews with people attending a Sarah Palin United States presidential election rally in St.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Clairsville, Ohio, with interviewees making comments about Barack Obama such as "he regards white people as trash" and "I'm afraid if he wins, the blacks will take over"...The report received over two million views on YouTube.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al-Jazeera, once viewed skeptically in the U.S, received broad praise for its Egypt coverage, which boosted its American audience and renewed calls for its inclusion on U.S. cable networks.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Additional programming geared towards an American audience includes a day's worth of special coverage marking the 10th anniversary of the terrorist attacks of 11 September 2001.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] Al Jazeera has also launched *The Stream*, a show based in Washington D.C. that discusses social media, which targets an American audience.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/al-jazeera-english] On 2 January 2013, Al Jazeera purchased the American channel Current TV and rebranded as Al Jazeera America in August 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The **Associated Press** (**AP**) is an American not-for-profit news agency headquartered in New York City.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Founded in 1846, it operates as a cooperative, unincorporated association, and produces news reports that are distributed to its members, major U.S. daily newspapers and radio and television broadcasters.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Since the Pulitzer Prize was established in 1917, the AP has earned 60 of them, including 36 for photography.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP distributes its widely used *AP Stylebook*, its AP polls tracking NCAA sports, and its election polls and results during U.S. elections.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] It sponsors the National Football League's annual awards.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] By 2016, news collected by the AP was published and republished by more than 1,300 newspapers and broadcasters.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP operates 235 news bureaus in 94 countries, and publishes in English, Spanish, and Arabic.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] It also operates the AP Radio Network, which provides twice hourly newscasts and daily sportscasts for broadcast and satellite radio and television stations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Many newspapers and broadcasters outside the United States are AP subscribers, paying a fee to use AP material without being contributing members of the cooperative.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] As part of their cooperative agreement with the AP, most member news organizations grant automatic permission for the AP to distribute their local news reports.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] As of 2025, the AP attracts more than 128 million monthly website visits, making it one of the top 10 news websites in the U.S.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The Associated Press was formed in May 1846 by five daily newspapers in New York City to share the cost of transmitting news of the Mexican–American War.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The venture was organized by Moses Yale Beach (1800–68), second publisher of *The Sun*, joined by the *New York Herald*, the *New York Courier and Enquirer*, *The Journal of Commerce*, and the *New York Evening Express*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Some historians believe that the *New-York Tribune* joined at this time; documents show it was a member in 1849.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] *The New York Times* became a member in September 1851.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Initially known as the New York Associated Press (NYAP), the organization faced competition from the Western Associated Press (1862), which criticized its monopolistic news gathering and price setting practices.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] An investigation completed in 1892 by Victor Lawson, editor and publisher of the *Chicago Daily News*, revealed that several principals of the NYAP entered into a secret agreement with United Press, a rival organization, to share NYAP news and the profits of reselling it.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The findings led to the dissolving of the NYAP.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] That December, the Western Associated Press was incorporated in Illinois as the Associated Press.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] A 1900 Illinois Supreme Court decision (*Inter Ocean Publishing Co. v.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Associated Press*) holding that the AP was a public utility and operating in restraint of trade resulted in the AP's move from Chicago to New York City, where corporation laws were more favorable to cooperatives.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 1935, the AP launched the Wirephoto network, which allowed transmission of news photographs over leased private telephone lines on the day they were taken.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] This gave the AP a major advantage over other news media outlets.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] While the first network was only between New York, Chicago, and San Francisco, eventually the AP had its network across the whole United States.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 1945, the Supreme Court of the United States held in *Associated Press v.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] United States* that the AP had been violating the Sherman Antitrust Act by prohibiting member newspapers from selling or providing news to nonmember organizations as well as making it very difficult for nonmember newspapers to join the AP.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP entered the broadcast field in 1941 when it began distributing news to radio stations; it created its own radio network in 1974.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 1994, it established APTV, a global video newsgathering agency.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] APTV merged with Worldwide Television News in 1998 to form APTN, which provides video to international broadcasters and websites.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2004, the AP moved its headquarters from its long-time home at 50 Rockefeller Plaza to 450 West 33rd Street in Manhattan.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2019, AP had more than 240 bureaus globally.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Its mission has not changed since its founding, but digital technology has made the distribution of the AP news report an interactive endeavor between the AP and its hundreds of U.S. newspaper members, as well as broadcasters, international subscribers, and online customers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP began diversifying its news gathering capabilities.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] By 2007, the AP was generating only about 30% of its revenue from United States newspapers, and by 2024, this had declined to 10%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] 37% came from the global broadcast customers, 15% from online ventures and 18% came from international newspapers and from photography.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In March 2024, Gannett, the largest U.S. newspaper publisher as measured by total daily circulation, announced that effective March 25, 2024, it would no longer use content from the AP.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] A spokesperson for AP said that they were "shocked and disappointed" by this development.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Newspaper chain McClatchy announced that it would also stop using some AP services.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Gannett and McClatchy will both continue to use AP's election results data.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP's multi-topic structure has resulted in web portals such as Yahoo! and MSN posting its articles, often relying on the AP as their first source for news coverage of breaking news items.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] This and the constant updating evolving stories require has had a major impact on the AP's public image and role, giving new credence to the AP's ongoing mission of having staff for covering every area of news fully and promptly.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2007, Google announced that it was paying to receive AP content, to be displayed in Google News, interrupted from late 2009 to mid-2010 due to a licensing dispute.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] A 2017 study by NewsWhip revealed that AP content was more engaged with on Facebook than content from any individual English-language publisher.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP is governed by an elected board of directors.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Since 2022, the board's chairperson is Gracia C.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Martore, former president and CEO of Tegna, Inc.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] AP reports from countries where press freedom is restricted, sometimes under adverse circumstances, and operates out of more than 100 regional offices.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2025, restrictions preventing AP reporting in the U.S. were imposed by the second Trump administration.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In February 2025, two AP reporters were barred from covering several events at the White House, because of the AP refusal to refer to the Gulf of Mexico as the "Gulf of America", as directed by the White House.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The restrictions against AP were extended to other reporting opportunities such as in Air Force One.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On February 21, 2025, the AP sued the Trump administration in *Associated Press v.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Budowich* for blocking their attendance.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On February 24, 2025, a federal judge declined to issue an immediate order compelling the White House to reinstate access to presidential events to AP, although he encouraged the White House to do so.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On April 8, 2025, Judge Trevor McFadden ruled that the White House must lift the access restrictions they placed on the AP while the *AP v.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On June 6, 2025, the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit imposed a stay upon the lower court's order, allowing the White House to resume barring access to some media events.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP is one of two organizations that collect and verify election results in every city and county across the United States, including races for the U.S. president, the Senate and House of Representatives, and governors as well as other statewide offices.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Known for accuracy, the organization has collected and published presidential election data since 1848.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Major news outlets rely on the polling data and results provided by the Associated Press before declaring a winner in major political races, particularly the presidential election.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In declaring the winners, the AP has historically relied on a robust network of local reporters with first-hand knowledge of assigned territories who also have long-standing relationships with county clerks as well as other local officials.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Moreover, the AP monitors and gathers data from county websites and electronic feeds provided by states.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The research team further verifies the results by considering demographics, number of absentee ballots, and other political issues that may have an effect on the final results.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2018, the AP introduced a new system called AP VoteCast, which was developed together with NORC at the University of Chicago in order to further improve the reliability of its data and overcome biases of its legacy exit poll.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP conducts polls for numerous college sports in the United States.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP college football rankings were created in 1936, and began including the top 25 teams in 1989.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Since 1969, the final poll of each season has been released after all bowl games have been played.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP released its all-time Top 25 in 2016.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] As of 2017, 22 different programs had finished in the number one spot of the poll since its inception.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In the pre-bowl game determination era, the AP poll was often used as the distinction for a national champion in football.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP college basketball poll has been used as a guide for which teams deserve national attention.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP first began its poll of college basketball teams in 1949, and has since conducted over 1,100 polls.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The college basketball poll started with 20 teams and was reduced to 10 during the 1960–61 college basketball season.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] It returned to 20 teams in 1968–69 and expanded to 25 beginning in 1989–90.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The final poll for each season is released prior to the conclusion of the NCAA tournament, so all data includes regular season games only.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2017, The AP released a list of the Top 100 teams of all time.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The poll counted poll appearances (one point) and No.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] 1 rankings (two points) to rank each team.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP began its Major League Baseball Manager of the Year Award in 1959, for a manager in each league.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] From 1984 to 2000, the award was given to one manager in all of MLB.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The winners were chosen by a national panel of AP baseball writers and radio men.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Every year, the AP releases the names of the winners of its AP College Basketball Player of the Year and AP College Basketball Coach of the Year awards.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] It also honors a group of All-American players.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 1994, London-based Associated Press Television (APTV) was founded to provide agency news material to television broadcasters.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 1998, the AP purchased Worldwide Television News (WTN) from the ABC News division of The Walt Disney Company, Nine Network Australia and ITN London.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP publishes 70,000 videos and 6,000 hours of live video per year, as of 2016.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The agency also provides seven simultaneous live video channels, AP Direct for broadcasters, and six live channels on AP Live Choice for broadcasters and digital publishers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP was the first news agency to launch a live video news service in 2003.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The first publicly available edition of the book was published in 1953.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The first modern edition was published in August 1977 by Lorenz Press.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Afterwards, various paperback editions were published by different publishers, including, among others, Turtleback Books, Penguin's Laurel Press, Pearson's Addison-Wesley, and Hachette's Perseus Books and Basic Books.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Recent editions are released in several formats, including paperback and flat-lying spiral-bound editions, as well as a digital e-book edition and an online subscription version.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Additionally, the *AP Stylebook* also provides English grammar recommendations through social media, including Twitter, Facebook, Pinterest, and Instagram.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] From 1977 to 2005, more than two million copies of the *AP Stylebook* were sold worldwide, with that number climbing to 2.5 million by 2011.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Writers in broadcasting, news, magazine publishing, marketing departments, and public relations firms traditionally adopt and apply AP grammar and punctuation styles.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP collaborated with Nazi Germany and gave it access to its photographic archives for its antisemitic Nazi propaganda.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] AP also cooperated with the Nazi regime through censorship.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2017, the German historian Norman Domeier of the University of Vienna brought to wider attention the deal between the AP and the Nazi government related to the interchange of press photos during the period in which the United States was at war with Nazi Germany.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] This relationship involved the Bureau Laux, run by the Waffen-SS photographer Helmut Laux.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The mechanism for this interchange involved a courier flying to Lisbon and back each day transporting photos from and for Nazi Germany's wartime enemy, the United States, via diplomatic pouch.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The transactions were initially conducted at the AP bureau under Luiz Lupi in Lisbon, and from 1944, when the exchange via Lisbon took too long, also at the AP bureau in Stockholm under Eddie Shanke.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Here, as a cover, the Swedish agency, Pressens Bild, was involved as an intermediary.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] An estimated 40,000 photos were exchanged between the enemies in this way.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP was kicked out of Nazi Germany when the United States entered World War II in December 1941.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Israeli journalist Matti Friedman accused the AP of killing a story he wrote about the "war of words", "between Israel and its critics in human rights organizations", in the aftermath of the 2008–2009 Gaza war.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On September 29, 2000, the first day of the Second Intifada, the AP published a photograph of a badly-bloodied young man behind whom a police officer could be seen with a baton raised in a menacing fashion; a gas station with Hebrew lettering could also be seen in the background.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP labelled it with the caption "An Israeli policeman and a Palestinian on the Temple Mount", and the picture and caption were subsequently published in several major American newspapers, including the *New York Times*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In reality, the injured man in the photograph was a Jewish yeshiva student from Chicago named Tuvia Grossman, and the police officer, a Druze named Gidon Tzefadi, was protecting Grossman from a Palestinian mob who had clubbed, stoned, and stabbed Grossman.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] There are also no gas stations with Hebrew lettering on the Temple Mount.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The episode is often cited by those who accuse the media of having an anti-Israel bias, and was the impetus for the founding of the pro-Israel group HonestReporting.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] After a letter from Grossman's father noted the error, the AP, the *New York Times*, and other papers published corrections; despite these corrections, the photograph continues to be used by critics of Israel as a symbol of Israeli aggression and violence.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] During the 2021 Israel–Palestine crisis, the Israeli army destroyed the al-Jalaa Highrise, a building housing the AP's Gaza offices and Al Jazeera offices.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Israel stated that the building housed Hamas military intelligence and had given advanced warning of the strike, and no civilians were harmed.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] AP CEO Gary Pruitt released a statement on May 16, stating that he "had no indication Hamas was in the building" and called on the Israeli government to provide the evidence.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On May 17, US secretary of state Antony Blinken said he had not seen any evidence that Hamas operated from the building housing the AP and Al Jazeera, but it is the job of others to handle intelligence matters.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Israel reportedly shared intelligence with American officials and U.S. president Joe Biden showing Hamas offices inside the building.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Reporters Without Borders asked the International Criminal Court to investigate the bombing as a possible war crime.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On June 8, the Israeli ambassador to the US, Gilad Erdan, met with AP CEO Gary Pruitt and vice president for foreign news, Ian Phillips, to discuss the operation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In coordination with the IDF, Erdan said the site was used by Hamas intelligence officials to develop and carry out electronic warfare operations, and that IDF did not suspect the AP was aware of the alleged covert Hamas presence.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] After the meeting the AP stated "We have yet to receive evidence to support these claims".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In May 2024, Israeli officials seized equipment broadcasting a live stream of Northern Gaza from the town of Sderot as part of a ban on Al Jazeera Media in Israel which had received footage from the broadcast.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The move was condemned by multiple journalism organizations, Israeli opposition politicians, and US government officials.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 1994, Tina Susman was on her fourth trip to Somalia, reporting for the AP.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] She was reporting on U.S. peacekeeping troops leaving the country.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Somali rebels outnumbered her bodyguards in Mogadishu, dragged her from her car in broad daylight, and held her for 20 days.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] She told *The Quill* that she believes being a woman was an advantage in her experience there.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP had requested news organizations including *The New York Times*, the *Chicago Tribune,* and *The Washington Post* to suppress the story to discourage the emboldening of the kidnappers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In September 2002, Washington, D.C. bureau reporter Christopher Newton, an AP reporter since 1994, was fired after he was accused of fabricating sources since 2000, including at least 40 people and organizations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Prior to his firing, Newton had been focused on writing about federal law enforcement while based at the Justice Department.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Some of the nonexistent agencies quoted in his stories included "Education Alliance", the "Institute for Crime and Punishment in Chicago", "Voice for the Disabled", and "People for Civil Rights".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In 2007, an FBI agent working in Seattle impersonated an AP journalist and infected the computer of a 15-year-old suspect with malicious surveillance software.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The incident sparked a strongly worded statement from the AP demanding that the bureau never impersonate a member of the news media again.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In September 2016, the incident resulted in a report by the Justice Department, which the AP said "effectively condone[d] the FBI's impersonation".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In December 2017, following a US court appearance, a judge ruled in favor of the AP in a lawsuit against the FBI for fraudulently impersonating a member of the news media in conjunction with the 2007 case.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In June 2008, the AP sent numerous DMCA take-down demands and threatened legal action against several blogs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP contended that the internet blogs were violating the AP's copyright by linking to AP material and using headlines and short summaries in those links.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Many bloggers and experts noted that the use of the AP news fell squarely under commonly accepted internet practices and within fair-use standards.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Others noted and demonstrated that the AP routinely takes similar excerpts from other sources, often without attribution or licenses.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP responded that it was defining standards regarding citations of AP news.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In March 2009, the AP counter-sued artist Shepard Fairey over his famous image of Barack Obama, saying the uncredited, uncompensated use of an AP photo violated copyright laws and signaled a threat to journalism.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Fairey had sued the AP the previous month over his artwork, titled "Obama Hope" and "Obama Progress", arguing that he did not violate copyright law because he dramatically changed the image.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The artwork, based on an April 2006 picture taken for the AP by Mannie Garcia, was a popular image during the 2008 presidential election and now hangs in the National Portrait Gallery in Washington, D.C.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] According to the AP's lawsuit filed in federal court in Manhattan, Fairey knowingly "misappropriated The AP's rights in that image".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The suit asked the court to award the AP profits made off the image and damages.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Fairey said he looked forward to "upholding the free expression rights at stake here" and disproving the AP's accusations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In January 2011, the suit was settled with neither side declaring their position to be wrong but agreeing to share reproduction rights and profits from Fairey's work.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In January 2008, the AP sued competitor All Headline News (AHN) claiming that AHN allegedly infringed on its copyrights and a contentious "quasi-property" right to facts.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP complaint asserted that AHN reporters had copied facts from AP news reports without permission and without paying a syndication fee.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] After AHN moved to dismiss all but the copyright claims set forth by the AP, a majority of the lawsuit was dismissed.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The case has been dismissed and both parties settled.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On April 23, 2013, hackers posted a tweet to AP's Twitter account about fictional attacks on the White House, falsely claiming that President Obama had been injured.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The hoax caused a flash crash on the American stock markets, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average briefly falling by 143 points.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On May 13, 2013, the AP announced that telephone records for 20 of their reporters during a two-month period in 2012 had been subpoenaed by the U.S.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Justice Department and described these acts as a "massive and unprecedented intrusion" into news-gathering operations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The DOJ did not direct subpoenas to the AP, instead going to their phone providers, including Verizon Wireless.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Attorney General Eric Holder testified under oath in front of the House Judiciary Committee that he recused himself from the leak investigations to avoid any appearance of a conflict of interest.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Holder said his Deputy Attorney General, James M.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Cole, was in charge of the AP investigation and would have ordered the subpoenas.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] On January 10, 2022, AP announced it would start selling non-fungible tokens (NFTs) of their photographs in partnership with a company named Xooa, with the proceeds being used to fund their operations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] One of the NFTs they promoted on Twitter on 24 February was an aerial shot depicting an overcrowded migrant boat in the Mediterranean Sea by Brazilian photojournalist Felipe Dana.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The sale received negative backlash from users and other journalists, with AP being accused of profiting off of human suffering and the picture choice being "dystopian" and "in extremely poor taste".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The tweet was subsequently deleted and the NFT, which was to be sold the next day, was pulled from market.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] Global director of media relations Lauren Easton apologized, saying "This was a poor choice of imagery for an NFT.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] It has not and will not be put up for auction ...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] AP's NFT marketplace is a very early pilot program, and we are immediately reviewing our efforts".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP has earned 59 Pulitzer Prizes, including 36 for photography, since the award was established in 1917.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] In May 2020, Dar Yasin, Mukhtar Khan, and Channi Anand of the AP were honored with the 2020 Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The choice caused controversy, because it was taken by some as questioning "India's legitimacy over Kashmir" as it had used the word "independence" in regard to revocation of Article 370.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/associated-press] The AP won an Oscar in 2024 for the documentary film *20 Days in Mariupol*, a first-person account of the early days of Russia's invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] Archaeological evidence indicates that Azraq has been occupied for hundreds of thousands of years, with the oldest known remains dating to the Lower Palaeolithic, around 500–300,000 years ago.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] The spring-fed oasis provided a more or less constant source of water throughout this period, and probably acted as a refugium for humans and other animals at times when the surrounding area dried out.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] The oasis itself changed as the climate fluctuated: at times a permanent lake, a marsh, or a seasonal playa.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] Protein residue analysis of tools at the site suggests that the people there butchered ducks, camels, bovines (probably aurochs), equines and rhinoceros (probably the narrow-nosed rhinoceros).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] During the Epipalaeolithic period the oasis was also an important focus of settlement.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] Azraq has long been an important settlement in a remote and now-arid desert area of Jordan.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] The strategic value of the town and its castle (Qasr Azraq) is that it lies in the middle of the Azraq oasis, the only permanent source of fresh water in approximately 12,000 km2 (4,600 sq mi) of desert.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] The town is also located on a major desert route that would have facilitated trade within the region.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] Nabatean period settlement activity has also been documented in the area.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] Qasr Azraq was built by the Romans in the 3rd century AD, and was heavily modified in the Middle Ages by the Mamluks.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] In the Umayyad period a water reservoir was constructed in southern Azraq.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] During the Arab Revolt in the early 20th century, Qasr Azraq was an important headquarters for T.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] The Azraq refugee camp, sheltering refugees of the Syrian Civil War, was opened in 2014 and is located 20 km (12 mi) west of Azraq.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] The site had been previously used during the Gulf War of 1990–91 as a transit camp for displaced Iraqis and Kuwaitis.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] According to the Jordan National Census of 2004, the population of Azraq was 9,021, of whom 7,625 (84.5%) were Jordanian citizens.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] Azraq is also the site of one of Jordan's seven protected nature reserve areas (set up by the Royal Society for the Conservation of Nature): the Azraq Wetlands Reserve in Azraq al-Janoubi (South Azraq).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-jordan] The separate and larger Shaumari reserve is about 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) south of the town.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The **Azraq refugee camp** is a refugee camp, located near Azraq, Jordan, built for refugees of the Syrian Civil War.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] It was developed, and is operated, by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in conjunction with the Government of Jordan.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] As of March 2016 it had over 32,000 refugees in it; by August 2019 that number was over 35,000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] By the time of the fall of the Assad regime, in December 2024, around 41,000 Syrians were believed to be housed in the Azraq refugee camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The site, located 20 kilometres (12 mi) west of Azraq in hot desert terrain and 90 kilometres (56 mi) from the Jordan–Syria border, had been previously used during the Gulf War of 1990–91 as a transit camp for displaced Iraqis and Kuwaitis.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The camp itself stretches for some 15 kilometres (9.3 mi).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The signature element of the new camp's appearance were the rows and rows of white cabins with insulation and sloping roofs, to be used as the shelters.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The shelters were built with zinc and steel in an effort to withstand the hot and windy conditions.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Cement and concrete was not used in the construction of the camp, to emphasize the point that Jordan has made that the camp is not intended to be permanent.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The camp was designed to overcome some of the problems that had been experienced at the overcrowded and trouble-ridden Zaatari refugee camp that was located closer to the border.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The facilities of the Azraq camp, such as health clinics and playgrounds for children, were structured in a decentralised manner, with the idea of emulating villages within the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] In particular, a goal was to support the preservation of the traditional social structures of Syrian communities.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Security concerns were also paramount in laying out the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The UNHCR head of the camp said in April 2014, "We've studied what's been done in Zaatari and other refugee camps around the world and tried to plan carefully.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The first refugees began arriving at it on 28 April 2014.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] When it opened it had shelter for 25,000 people with an infrastructure intended for some 50,000, further expandable up to 130,000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] It thus had the potential to become one of the largest refugee camps not just around Syria but in the world, perhaps only second to the Dadaab camp in Kenya.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] At that time Jordan already had some 600,000 registered refugees within its borders, with that country's officials saying the real number could be twice that.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Once open, the camp did not become populated to the extent expected.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] By March 2015 the Azraq refugee camp had only 14,500 refugees, when it had been anticipated there would be over 60,000 by then.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Some of the reasons were external, such as fear of Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant fighters entering Jordan along with refugees or the Jordanian government worried about possible donor fatigue and the long-term expense of housing a refugee population.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] But other reasons were due to the camp itself: more than half of the 35,000 refugees who had entered the camp had already left (most would settle illegally in Jordanian towns and cities).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] One early issue at the camp was the absence of electricity, due to the remoteness of the camp from other populated areas.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Refugees thus had to make use of solar lanterns instead.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Among other effects, this made it difficult for refugees to keep their mobile phones charged and thus stay in contact with family members outside the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Gradually a few generators became available.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Other refugees worried about mice, snakes, and scorpions.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The desolate nature of the camp worked against itself; as one elderly refugee said when he arrived with his relatives, "When I first arrived and saw the camp, I almost had a heart attack.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] By June 2015 the Azraq refugee camp still had only around 18,500 refugees in it.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] The most commonly cited reasons for refugees not wanting to stay there were very hot temperatures in the summer months, continued chronic absences of electricity, and high food prices.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Some refugees in the camp received permits to visit Jordanian cities and then never returned.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] As the Syrian refugee crisis attained global public awareness in late 2015, the state of the Azraq refugee camp became involved in political considerations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] In November 2015, retired neurosurgeon Ben Carson visited the camp, as part of trying to bolster his foreign policy expertise during his 2016 U.S. presidential campaign.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] He concluded that rather than refugees coming to the United States, they should be sheltered in nearby countries in the Middle East.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Population of the camp gradually increased throughout the second half of 2015, but remained well below initial expectations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] By early 2016, another problem with filling the camp were the large numbers of refugees being held up at a military-controlled area along the border with Syria where there was slow processing of them due to security and other reasons.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Efforts to improve the electricity situation at the camp continued, with a 6-megawatt, $10 million solar power project underway, the first parts of which were scheduled to come online in mid-2016.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] In March 2019 the Women and Girls Safe Space Centre was opened within the camp by the Danish Refugee Council.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] With activities including protection awareness, support groups, and recreational and financial skills training activities, it proved to be a popular resource within the camp.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] By then the camp's population numbered over 35,000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Following the fall of the Assad regime in Syria, many residents expressed hope at being able to return to their home country, and a number of refugees departed the camp to return to their homes.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Nevertheless, the situation has been complicated by the precarious economic and security situation in Syria, with some returning refugees expressing concern at the lack of housing or economic opportunities in the country.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] Because of this, the number of refugees who hoped to be able to return to Syria dropped from 68% in a poll in January 2025 to 32% by April 2025.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/azraq-refugee-camp] In July 2025 it was reported that UNICEF along with the UK's Foreign, Commonwealth & Development Office (FCDO), signed a new £1.5 million agreement, that will ensure the continuity of water supply to the refugees.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 2019, it was reported in an Ofcom report that the BBC spent £136m on news during the period April 2018 to March 2019.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News' domestic, global and online news divisions are housed within the largest live newsroom in Europe, in Broadcasting House in central London.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Parliamentary coverage is produced and broadcast from studios in London.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Through BBC English Regions, the BBC also has regional centres across England and national news centres in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] All nations and English regions produce their own local news programmes and other current affairs and sport programmes.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC is a quasi-autonomous corporation authorised by royal charter, making it operationally independent of the government.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] As of 2024, the BBC reaches an average of 450 million people per week, with the BBC World Service accounting for 320 million people.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The British Broadcasting Company broadcast its first radio bulletin from radio station 2LO on 14 November 1922.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Wishing to avoid competition, newspaper publishers persuaded the government to ban the BBC from broadcasting news before 7 pm, and to force it to use wire service copy instead of reporting on its own.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC gradually gained the right to edit the copy and, in 1934, created its own news operation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] However, it could not broadcast news before 6 p.m. until World War II.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In addition to news, Gaumont British and Movietone cinema newsreels had been broadcast on the TV service since 1936, with the BBC producing its own equivalent *Television Newsreel* programme from January 1948.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] A weekly *Children's Newsreel* was inaugurated on 23 April 1950, to around 350,000 receivers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The network began simulcasting its radio news on television in 1946, with a still picture of Big Ben.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Televised bulletins began on 5 July 1954, broadcast from leased studios within Alexandra Palace in London.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The public's interest in television and live events was stimulated by Elizabeth II's coronation in 1953.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] It is estimated that up to 27 million people viewed the programme in the UK, overtaking radio's audience of 12 million for the first time.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Those live pictures were fed from 21 cameras in central London to Alexandra Palace for transmission, and then on to other UK transmitters opened in time for the event.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] That year, there were around two million TV Licences held in the UK, rising to over three million the following year, and four and a half million by 1955.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Television news, although physically separate from its radio counterpart, was still firmly under radio news' control in the 1950s.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Correspondents provided reports for both outlets, and the first televised bulletin, shown on 5 July 1954 on the then BBC television service and presented by Richard Baker, involved his providing narration off-screen while stills were shown.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This was then followed by the customary *Television Newsreel* with a recorded commentary by John Snagge (and on other occasions by Andrew Timothy).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On-screen newsreaders were introduced a year later in 1955 – Kenneth Kendall (the first to appear in vision), Robert Dougall, and Richard Baker—three weeks before ITN's launch on 21 September 1955.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Mainstream television production had started to move out of Alexandra Palace in 1950 to larger premises – mainly at Lime Grove Studios in Shepherd's Bush, west London – taking Current Affairs (then known as Talks Department) with it.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] It was from here that the first *Panorama*, a new documentary programme, was transmitted on 11 November 1953, with Richard Dimbleby becoming anchor in 1955.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 1958, Hugh Carleton Greene became head of News and Current Affairs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On 1 January 1960, Greene became Director-General.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Greene made changes that were aimed at making BBC reporting more similar to its competitor ITN, which had been highly rated by study groups held by Greene.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] A newsroom was created at Alexandra Palace, television reporters were recruited and given the opportunity to write and voice their own scripts, without having to cover stories for radio too.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On 20 June 1960, Nan Winton, the first female BBC network newsreader, appeared in vision.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] 19 September 1960 saw the start of the radio news and current affairs programme *The Ten O'clock News*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC2 started transmission on 20 April 1964 and began broadcasting a new show, *Newsroom*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On Sunday 17 September 1967, *The World This Weekend*, a weekly news and current affairs programme, launched on what was then Home Service, but soon-to-be Radio 4.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Preparations for colour began in the autumn of 1967 and on Thursday 7 March 1968 *Newsroom* on BBC2 moved to an early evening slot, becoming the first UK news programme to be transmitted in colour – from Studio A at Alexandra Palace.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] *News Review* and *Westminster* (the latter a weekly review of Parliamentary happenings) were "colourised" shortly after.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] However, much of the insert material was still in black and white, as initially only a part of the film coverage shot in and around London was on colour reversal film stock, and all regional and many international contributions were still in black and white.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Colour facilities at Alexandra Palace were technically very limited for the next eighteen months, as it had only one RCA colour Quadruplex videotape machine and, eventually two Pye plumbicon colour telecines–although the news colour service started with just one.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] *Town and Around* was never to make the move to Television Centre – instead it became *London This Week* which aired on Mondays and Fridays only, from the new TVC studios.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC moved production out of Alexandra Palace in 1969.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC Television News resumed operations the next day with a lunchtime bulletin on BBC1 – in black and white – from Television Centre, where it remained until March 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This move to a smaller studio with better technical facilities allowed *Newsroom* and *News Review* to replace back projection with colour-separation overlay.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] During the 1960s, satellite communication had become possible; however, it was some years before digital line-store conversion was able to undertake the process seamlessly.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On 14 September 1970, the first *Nine O'Clock News* was broadcast on television.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Robert Dougall presented the first week from studio N1 – described by *The Guardian* as "a sort of polystyrene padded cell"—the bulletin having been moved from the earlier time of 20.50 as a response to the ratings achieved by ITN's *News at Ten*, introduced three years earlier on the rival ITV.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Richard Baker and Kenneth Kendall presented subsequent weeks, thus echoing those first television bulletins of the mid-1950s.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Angela Rippon became the first female news presenter of the *Nine O'Clock News* in 1975.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Her work outside the news was controversial at the time, appearing on *The Morecambe and Wise Christmas Show* in 1976 singing and dancing.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The first edition of *John Craven's Newsround*, initially intended only as a short series and later renamed just *Newsround*, came from studio N3 on 4 April 1972.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Afternoon television news bulletins during the mid to late 1970s were broadcast from the BBC newsroom itself, rather than one of the three news studios.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The newsreader would present to camera while sitting on the edge of a desk; behind him staff would be seen working busily at their desks.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This period corresponded with when the *Nine O'Clock News* got its next makeover, and would use a CSO background of the newsroom from that very same camera each weekday evening.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Also in the mid-1970s, the late night news on BBC2 was briefly renamed *Newsnight*, but this was not to last, or be the same programme as we know today – that would be launched in 1980 – and it soon reverted to being just a news summary with the early evening BBC2 news expanded to become *Newsday*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] News on radio was to change in the 1970s, and on Radio 4 in particular, brought about by the arrival of new editor Peter Woon from television news and the implementation of the *Broadcasting in the Seventies* report.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] These included the introduction of correspondents into news bulletins where previously only a newsreader would present, as well as the inclusion of content gathered in the preparation process.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] New programmes were also added to the daily schedule, *PM* and *The World Tonight* as part of the plan for the station to become a "wholly speech network".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] *Newsbeat* launched as the news service on Radio 1 on 10 September 1973.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On 23 September 1974, a teletext system which was launched to bring news content on television screens using text only was launched.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Engineers originally began developing such a system to bring news to deaf viewers, but the system was expanded.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The Ceefax service became much more diverse before it ceased on 23 October 2012: it not only had subtitling for all channels, it also gave information such as weather, flight times and film reviews.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] By the end of the decade, the practice of shooting on film for inserts in news broadcasts was declining, with the introduction of ENG technology into the UK.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The equipment would gradually become less cumbersome – the BBC's first attempts had been using a Philips colour camera with backpack base station and separate portable Sony U-matic recorder in the latter half of the decade.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 1980, the Iranian Embassy Siege had been shot electronically by the BBC Television News Outside broadcasting team, and the work of reporter Kate Adie, broadcasting live from Prince's Gate, was nominated for BAFTA actuality coverage, but this time beaten by ITN for the 1980 award.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The first BBC breakfast television programme, *Breakfast Time* also launched during the 1980s, on 17 January 1983 from Lime Grove Studio E and two weeks before its ITV rival TV-am.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Frank Bough, Selina Scott, and Nick Ross helped to wake viewers with a relaxed style of presenting.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* first aired on 3 September 1984, eventually becoming the most watched news programme in the UK (however, since 2006 it has been overtaken by the *BBC News at Ten*).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In October 1984, images of millions of people starving to death in the Ethiopian famine were shown in Michael Buerk's *Six O'Clock News* reports.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC News crew were the first to document the famine, with Buerk's report on 23 October describing it as "a biblical famine in the 20th century" and "the closest thing to hell on Earth".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC News report shocked Britain, motivating its citizens to inundate relief agencies, such as Save the Children, with donations, and to bring global attention to the crisis in Ethiopia.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The news report was also watched by Bob Geldof, who would organise the charity single "Do They Know It's Christmas?" to raise money for famine relief followed by the Live Aid concert in July 1985.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Starting in 1981, the BBC gave a common theme to its main news bulletins with new electronic titles–a set of computer-animated "stripes" forming a circle on a red background with a "BBC News" typescript appearing below the circle graphics, and a theme tune consisting of brass and keyboards.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The *Nine* used a similar (striped) number 9.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The red background was replaced by a blue from 1985 until 1987.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 1987, John Birt resurrected the practice of correspondents working for both TV and radio with the introduction of bi-media journalism.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] During the 1990s, a wider range of services began to be offered by BBC News, with the split of BBC World Service Television to become BBC World (news and current affairs), and BBC Prime (light entertainment).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Content for a 24-hour news channel was thus required, followed in 1997 with the launch of domestic equivalent BBC News 24.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Rather than set bulletins, ongoing reports and coverage was needed to keep both channels functioning and meant a greater emphasis in budgeting for both was necessary.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 1998, after 66 years at Broadcasting House, the **BBC Radio News** operation moved to BBC Television Centre.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] New technology, provided by Silicon Graphics, came into use in 1993 for a re-launch of the main BBC 1 bulletins, creating a virtual set which appeared to be much larger than it was physically.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The relaunch also brought all bulletins into the same style of set with only small changes in colouring, titles, and music to differentiate each.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] A computer generated cut-glass sculpture of the BBC coat of arms was the centrepiece of the programme titles until the large scale corporate rebranding of news services in 1999.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In November 1997, BBC News Online was launched, following individual webpages for major news events such as the 1996 Olympic Games, 1997 general election, and the death of Princess Diana.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 1999, the biggest relaunch occurred, with BBC One bulletins, BBC World, BBC News 24, and BBC News Online all adopting a common style.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] One of the most significant changes was the gradual adoption of the corporate image by the BBC regional news programmes, giving a common style across local, national and international BBC television news.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This also included *Newyddion*, the main news programme of Welsh language channel S4C, produced by BBC News Wales.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Following the relaunch of BBC News in 1999, regional headlines were included at the start of the BBC One news bulletins in 2000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The English regions did however lose five minutes at the end of their bulletins, due to a new headline round-up at 18:55.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] 2000 also saw the *Nine O'Clock News* moved to the later time of 22:00.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This was in response to ITN who had just moved their popular *News at Ten* programme to 23:00.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] ITN briefly returned *News at Ten* but following poor ratings when head-to-head against the BBC's *Ten O'Clock News*, the ITN bulletin was moved to 22.30, where it remained until 14 January 2008.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The retirement in 2009 of Peter Sissons and departure of Michael Buerk from the *Ten O'Clock News* led to changes in the BBC One bulletin presenting team on 20 January 2003.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The *Six O'Clock News* became double headed with George Alagiah and Sophie Raworth after Huw Edwards and Fiona Bruce moved to present the *Ten*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] A new set design featuring a projected fictional newsroom backdrop was introduced, followed on 16 February 2004 by new programme titles to match those of BBC News 24.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News 24 and BBC World introduced a new style of presentation in December 2003, that was slightly altered on 5 July 2004 to mark 50 years of BBC Television News.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The individual positions of editor of the *One* and *Six O'Clock News* were replaced by a new daytime position in November 2005.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Kevin Bakhurst became the first Controller of BBC News 24, replacing the position of editor.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Amanda Farnsworth became daytime editor while Craig Oliver was later named editor of the *Ten O'Clock News*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Bulletins received new titles and a new set design in May 2006, to allow for *Breakfast* to move into the main studio for the first time since 1997.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The new set featured Barco videowall screens with a background of the London skyline used for main bulletins and originally an image of cirrus clouds against a blue sky for *Breakfast*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This was later replaced following viewer criticism.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The studio bore similarities with the ITN-produced ITV News in 2004, though ITN uses a CSO virtual studio rather than the actual screens at BBC News.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News became part of a new BBC Journalism group in November 2006 as part of a restructuring of the BBC.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The then-Director of BBC News, Helen Boaden reported to the then-Deputy Director-General and head of the journalism group, Mark Byford until he was made redundant in 2010.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On 18 October 2007, ED Mark Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures" (based on his project begun in March 2005), merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The various separate newsrooms for television, radio and online operations were merged into a single multimedia newsroom.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Programme making within the newsrooms was brought together to form a multimedia programme making department.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC World Service director Peter Horrocks said that the changes would achieve efficiency at a time of cost-cutting at the BBC.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In his blog, he wrote that by using the same resources across the various broadcast media meant fewer stories could be covered, or by following more stories, there would be fewer ways to broadcast them.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] A new graphics and video playout system was introduced for production of television bulletins in January 2007.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This coincided with a new structure to BBC World News bulletins, editors favouring a section devoted to analysing the news stories reported on.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The first new BBC News bulletin since the *Six O'Clock News* was announced in July 2007 following a successful trial in the Midlands.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The summary, lasting 90 seconds, has been broadcast at 20:00 on weekdays since December 2007 and bears similarities with *60 Seconds* on BBC Three, but also includes headlines from the various BBC regions and a weather summary.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] As part of a long-term cost cutting programme, bulletins were renamed the *BBC News at One*, *Six* and *Ten* respectively in April 2008 while BBC News 24 was renamed BBC News and moved into the same studio as the bulletins at BBC Television Centre.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC World was renamed *BBC World News* and regional news programmes were also updated with the new presentation style, designed by Lambie-Nairn.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] 2008 also saw tri-media introduced across TV, radio, and online.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The studio moves also meant that Studio N9, previously used for BBC World, was closed, and operations moved to the previous studio of BBC News 24.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Studio N9 was later refitted to match the new branding, and was used for the BBC's UK local elections and European elections coverage in early June 2009.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] A strategy review of the BBC in March 2010, confirmed that having "the best journalism in the world" would form one of five key editorial policies, as part of changes subject to public consultation and BBC Trust approval.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] After a period of suspension in late 2012, Helen Boaden ceased to be the Director of BBC News.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On 16 April 2013, incoming BBC Director-General Tony Hall named James Harding, a former editor of *The Times* of London newspaper as Director of News and Current Affairs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] From August 2012 to March 2013, all news operations moved from Television Centre to new facilities in the refurbished and extended Broadcasting House, in Portland Place.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The move began in October 2012, and also included the BBC World Service, which moved from Bush House following the expiry of the BBC's lease.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This new extension to the north and east, referred to as "New Broadcasting House", includes several new state-of-the-art radio and television studios centred around an 11-storey atrium.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The move began with the domestic programme *The Andrew Marr Show* on 2 September 2012, and concluded with the move of the BBC News channel and domestic news bulletins on 18 March 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The newsroom houses all domestic bulletins and programmes on both television and radio, as well as the BBC World Service international radio networks and the BBC World News international television channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News and CBS News established an editorial and newsgathering partnership in 2017, replacing an earlier long-standing partnership between BBC News and ABC News.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In an October 2018 Simmons Research survey of 38 news organisations, BBC News was ranked the fourth most trusted news organisation by Americans, behind CBS News, ABC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In January 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 450 staff reductions from the current 6,000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] A further 70 staff reductions were announced in July 2020.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC Three began airing the news programme *The Catch Up* in February 2022.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] It is presented by Levi Jouavel, Kirsty Grant, and Callum Tulley and aims to get the channel's target audience (16 to 34-year olds) to make sense of the world around them while also highlighting optimistic stories.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Compared to its predecessor *60 Seconds*, *The Catch Up* is three times longer, running for about three minutes and not airing during weekends.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] According to its annual report as of December 2021, India has the largest number of people using BBC services in the world.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In May 2025, following the earthquake that hit Myanmar and Thailand, a television news bulletin (BBC News Myanmar) from the Burmese service using a vacated Voice of America satellite frequency began its broadcasts.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Government officials including Cyprus president Nikos Christodoulides and European lawmakers began responding to the investigation's findings in less than 24 hours, calling for reforms and launching probes.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News is responsible for the news programmes and documentary content on the BBC's general television channels, as well as the news coverage on the BBC News Channel in the UK, and 22 hours of programming for the corporation's international BBC World News channel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Coverage for BBC Parliament is carried out on behalf of the BBC at Millbank Studios, though BBC News provides editorial and journalistic content.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News content is also output onto the BBC's digital interactive television services under the BBC Red Button brand, and until 2012, on the Ceefax teletext system.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The music on all BBC television news programmes was introduced in 1999 and composed by David Lowe.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] It was part of the re-branding which commenced in 1999 and features 'BBC Pips'.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The general theme was used on bulletins on BBC One, News 24, BBC World and local news programmes in the BBC's Nations and Regions.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Lowe was also responsible for the music on Radio One's *Newsbeat*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The theme has had several changes since 1999, the latest in March 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC Verify service was launched in 2023 to fact-check news stories, followed by BBC Verify Live in 2025.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC Radio News produces bulletins for the BBC's national radio stations and provides content for local BBC radio stations via the General News Service (GNS), a BBC-internal news distribution service.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News does not produce the BBC's regional news bulletins, which are produced individually by the BBC nations and regions themselves.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC World Service broadcasts to some 150 million people in English as well as 27 languages across the globe.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC Radio News is a patron of the Radio Academy.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News Online is the BBC's news website.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Launched in November 1997, it is one of the most popular news websites, with 1.2 billion website visits in April 2021, as well as being used by 60% of the UK's internet users for news.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The website contains international news coverage as well as entertainment, sport, science, and political news.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Mobile apps for Android, iOS and Windows Phone systems have been provided since 2010.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Many television and radio programmes are also available to view on the BBC iPlayer and BBC Sounds services.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC News channel is also available to view 24 hours a day, while video and radio clips are also available within online news articles.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In October 2019, BBC News Online launched a mirror on the dark web anonymity network Tor in an effort to circumvent censorship.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC is required by its charter to be free from both political and commercial influence and answers only to its viewers and listeners.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] This political objectivity is sometimes questioned.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] For instance, *The Daily Telegraph* (3 August 2005) carried a letter from the KGB defector Oleg Gordievsky, referring to it as "The Red Service".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Books have been written on the subject, including anti-BBC works like *Truth Betrayed* by W J West and *The Truth Twisters* by Richard Deacon.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC has been accused of bias by Conservative MPs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC's Editorial Guidelines on Politics and Public Policy state that while "the voices and opinions of opposition parties must be routinely aired and challenged", "the government of the day will often be the primary source of news".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC is regularly accused by the government of the day of bias in favour of the opposition and, by the opposition, of bias in favour of the government.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Similarly, during times of war, the BBC is often accused by the UK government, or by strong supporters of British military campaigns, of being overly sympathetic to the view of the enemy.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] An edition of *Newsnight* at the start of the Falklands War in 1982 was described as "almost treasonable" by John Page, MP, who objected to Peter Snow saying "if we believe the British".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] During the first Gulf War, critics of the BBC took to using the satirical name "Baghdad Broadcasting Corporation".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Conversely, some of those who style themselves anti-establishment in the United Kingdom or who oppose foreign wars have accused the BBC of pro-establishment bias or of refusing to give an outlet to "anti-war" voices.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Following the 2003 invasion of Iraq, a study by the Cardiff University School of Journalism of the reporting of the war found that nine out of 10 references to weapons of mass destruction during the war assumed that Iraq possessed them, and only one in 10 questioned this assumption.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] It also found that, out of the main British broadcasters covering the war, the BBC was the most likely to use the British government and military as its source.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] It was also the least likely to use independent sources, like the Red Cross, who were more critical of the war.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] When it came to reporting Iraqi casualties, the study found fewer reports on the BBC than on the other three main channels.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The report's author, Justin Lewis, wrote "Far from revealing an anti-war BBC, our findings tend to give credence to those who criticised the BBC for being too sympathetic to the government in its war coverage.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Prominent BBC appointments are constantly assessed by the British media and political establishment for signs of political bias.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The appointment of Greg Dyke as Director-General was highlighted by press sources because Dyke was a Labour Party member and former activist, as well as a friend of Tony Blair.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Mark Thompson, former Director-General of the BBC, admitted the organisation has been biased "towards the left" in the past.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] He said, "In the BBC I joined 30 years ago, there was, in much of current affairs, in terms of people's personal politics, which were quite vocal, a massive bias to the left".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] He then added, "The organization did struggle then with impartiality.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Now it is a completely different generation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Following the EU referendum in 2016, some critics suggested that the BBC was biased in favour of leaving the EU.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] For instance, in 2018, the BBC received complaints from people who took issue that the BBC was not sufficiently covering anti-Brexit marches while giving smaller-scale events hosted by former UKIP leader Nigel Farage more airtime.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] On the other hand, a poll released by YouGov showed that 45% of people who voted to leave the EU thought that the BBC was 'actively anti-Brexit' compared to 13% of the same kinds of voters who think the BBC is pro-Brexit.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 2008, the BBC Hindi was criticised by some Indian outlets for referring to the terrorists who carried out the 2008 Mumbai attacks as "gunmen".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The response to this added to prior criticism from some Indian commentators suggesting that the BBC may have an Indophobic bias.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In March 2015, the BBC was criticised for a BBC *Storyville* documentary interviewing one of the rapists in India.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In spite of a ban ordered by the Indian High court, the BBC still aired the documentary "India's Daughter" outside India.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News was at the centre of a political controversy following the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The government denounced the reports and accused the corporation of poor journalism.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In subsequent weeks the corporation stood by the report, saying that it had a reliable source.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Following intense media speculation, David Kelly was named in the press as the source for Gilligan's story on 9 July 2003.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Kelly was found dead, by suicide, in a field close to his home early on 18 July.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] An inquiry led by Lord Hutton was announced by the British government the following day to investigate the circumstances leading to Kelly's death, concluding that "Dr.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In his report on 28 January 2004, Lord Hutton concluded that Gilligan's original accusation was "unfounded" and the BBC's editorial and management processes were "defective".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In particular, it specifically criticised the chain of management that caused the BBC to defend its story.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC Director of News, Richard Sambrook, the report said, had accepted Gilligan's word that his story was accurate in spite of his notes being incomplete.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Davies had then told the BBC Board of Governors that he was happy with the story and told the Prime Minister that a satisfactory internal inquiry had taken place.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The Board of Governors, under the chairman's, Gavyn Davies, guidance, accepted that further investigation of the Government's complaints were unnecessary.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Because of the criticism in the Hutton report, Davies resigned on the day of publication.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News faced an important test, reporting on itself with the publication of the report, but by common consent (of the Board of Governors) managed this "independently, impartially and honestly".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Davies' resignation was followed by the resignation of Director General, Greg Dyke, the following day, and the resignation of Gilligan on 30 January.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] While undoubtedly a traumatic experience for the corporation, an ICM poll in April 2003 indicated that it had sustained its position as the best and most trusted provider of news.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC has faced accusations of holding both anti-Israel and anti-Palestine bias.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] However two large independent studies, one conducted by Loughborough University and the other by Glasgow University's Media Group concluded that Israeli perspectives are given greater coverage.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Critics of the BBC argue that the Balen Report proves systematic bias against Israel in headline news programming.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The *Daily Mail* and *The Daily Telegraph* criticised the BBC for spending hundreds of thousands of British tax payers' pounds from preventing the report being released to the public.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] An independent panel appointed by the BBC Trust was set up in 2006 to review the impartiality of the BBC's coverage of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In some ways the picture is incomplete and, in that sense, misleading." It notes that, "the failure to convey adequately the disparity in the Israeli and Palestinian experience, [reflects] the fact that one side is in control and the other lives under occupation".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Writing in the *Financial Times*, Philip Stephens, one of the panellists, later accused the BBC's director-general, Mark Thompson, of misrepresenting the panel's conclusions.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] He further opined "My sense is that BBC news reporting has also lost a once iron-clad commitment to objectivity and a necessary respect for the democratic process.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Mark Thompson published a rebuttal in the FT the next day.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Walker argues that the independent inquiry was flawed for two reasons.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Firstly, because the time period over which it was conducted (August 2005 to January 2006) surrounded the Israeli withdrawal from Gaza and Ariel Sharon's stroke, which produced more positive coverage than usual.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Furthermore, he wrote, the inquiry only looked at the BBC's domestic coverage, and excluded output on the BBC World Service and BBC World.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Tom Gross, writing for the *National Review*, criticised the BBC's coverage of Hamas suicide bombers, and its invitations of Jenny Tonge and Tom Paulin as guest commentators, claiming that Paulin had "compared Jewish settlers to Nazis".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Paulin had previously stated that Israeli settlers should be "shot dead", and said he could "understand how suicide bombers feel".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC also faced criticism for not airing a Disasters Emergency Committee aid appeal for Palestinians who suffered in Gaza during 22-day war there between late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Most other major UK broadcasters did air this appeal, but rival Sky News did not.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] British journalist Julie Burchill has accused BBC of creating a "climate of fear" for British Jews over its "excessive coverage" of Israel compared to other nations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In light of the Gaza war, the BBC suspended seven Arab journalists over allegations of expressing support for Hamas via social media.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC and ABC share video segments and reporters as needed in producing their newscasts. with the BBC showing *ABC World News Tonight with David Muir* in the UK.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] However, in July 2017, the BBC announced a new partnership with CBS News allows both organisations to share video, editorial content, and additional newsgathering resources in New York, London, Washington and around the world.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News subscribes to wire services from leading international agencies including PA Media (formerly Press Association), Reuters, and Agence France-Presse.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In April 2017, the BBC dropped Associated Press in favour of an enhanced service from AFP.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC News reporters and broadcasts are now and have in the past been banned in several countries primarily for reporting which has been unfavourable to the ruling government.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] For example, correspondents were banned by the former apartheid regime of South Africa.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Zimbabwe under Mugabe for eight years as a terrorist organisation until being allowed to operate again over a year after the 2008 elections.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC was banned in Burma (officially Myanmar) after their coverage and commentary on anti-government protests there in September 2007.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The ban was lifted four years later in September 2011.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Other cases have included Uzbekistan, China, and Pakistan.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] BBC Persian, the BBC's Persian language news site, was blocked from the Iranian internet in 2006.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The BBC News website was made available in China again in March 2008, but as of October 2014, was blocked again.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In June 2015, the Rwandan government placed an indefinite ban on BBC broadcasts following the airing of a controversial documentary regarding the 1994 Rwandan genocide, *Rwanda's Untold Story*, broadcast on BBC2 on 1 October 2014.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] The UK's Foreign Office recognised "the hurt caused in Rwanda by some parts of the documentary".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In February 2017, reporters from the BBC (as well as the *Daily Mail*, *The New York Times*, Politico, CNN, and others) were denied access to a United States White House briefing.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] In 2017, BBC India was banned for a period of five years from covering all national parks and sanctuaries in India.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/bbc-news] Following the withdrawal of CGTN's UK broadcaster licence on 4 February 2021 by Ofcom, China banned BBC News from airing in China.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson became the youngest chief of pediatric neurosurgery in the United States in 1984, when he took the job at the Johns Hopkins Children's Center at age 33.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1987, he gained fame for leading a team of surgeons in the first-known separation of conjoined twins joined at the back of the head.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He performed the first successful neurosurgical procedure on a fetus inside the womb, developed new methods to treat brain-stem tumors, and revitalized hemispherectomy techniques for controlling seizures.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He has written more than 100 neurosurgical publications.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He retired from medicine in 2013; at the time, he was professor of neurosurgery, oncology, plastic surgery, and pediatrics at the Johns Hopkins School of Medicine.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson gained national fame among political conservatives after delivering a speech at the 2013 National Prayer Breakfast that was perceived as critical of the policies of President Barack Obama.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] After widespread speculation about a presidential run, Carson announced his campaign for the 2016 Republican nomination for president in May 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson performed strongly in early polls and was considered a frontrunner for the nomination in fall 2015, but did poorly in the primaries and withdrew from the race after Super Tuesday.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He subsequently endorsed Donald Trump, who as president nominated him to be secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He was confirmed by the United States Senate, 58–41, on March 2, 2017.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson has received numerous honors for his neurosurgery work, including more than 70 honorary doctorate degrees and numerous national merit citations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 2001, he was named by CNN and *Time* magazine as one of the nation's 20 foremost physicians and scientists and was named by the Library of Congress as one of 89 "Living Legends" on its 200th anniversary.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 2008, Carson was bestowed the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the highest civilian award in the United States.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 2010, he was elected to the National Academy of Medicine.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He was the subject of the 2009 biographical television film *Gifted Hands: The Ben Carson Story*, in which he was portrayed by Cuba Gooding Jr.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson's parents were Robert Solomon Carson Jr.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Army veteran, and Sonya Carson (née Copeland, 1928–2017).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Both from large families in rural Georgia, Carson's parents met and married while living in rural Tennessee, when his mother was 13 and his father 28.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] After Robert's completion of military service, they moved from Chattanooga, Tennessee, to Detroit, Michigan, where they lived in a large house in the Indian Village neighborhood.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson's father, a Baptist minister, worked in a Cadillac automobile plant.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] His older brother, Curtis, was born in 1949, when his mother was 20.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1950, Carson's parents purchased a new 733-square-foot single-family detached home on Deacon Street in the Boynton neighborhood of southwest Detroit, where Carson was born on September 18, 1951.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson's Detroit Public Schools education began in 1956 with kindergarten at the Fisher School and continued through first, second, and the first half of third grade, during which time he was an average student.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] When Carson was five years old, his mother learned that his father had a prior family and had not divorced his first wife.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1959, when he was eight, his parents separated and he moved with his mother and brother to live for two years with his mother's Seventh-day Adventist older sister and brother-in-law in multi-family dwellings in the Dorchester and Roxbury neighborhoods of Boston.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1961, at the age of 10, Carson moved with his mother and brother back to southwest Detroit, where they lived in a multi-family dwelling in a primarily white neighborhood, Springwells Village, while renting out their house on Deacon Street, which his mother had received in her divorce settlement.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson attended the predominantly white Higgins Elementary School for fifth and sixth grades and the predominantly white Wilson Junior High School for seventh and the first half of eighth grade.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1965, at the age of 13, he moved with his mother and brother back to their house on Deacon Street.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He attended the predominantly black Hunter Junior High School for the second half of eighth grade.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] At the age of eight, Carson dreamt of becoming a missionary doctor, but five years later he aspired to the lucrative lifestyles of psychiatrists portrayed on television, and his brother bought him a subscription to *Psychology Today* for his 13th birthday.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] By grade 9, the family's financial situation had improved.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] His mother surprised neighbors by paying cash to buy a new Chrysler car, and the only government assistance they still relied on was food stamps.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson attended the predominantly black Southwestern High School for grades nine through twelve, graduating third in his class academically.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In high school, he played the euphonium in band and participated in forensics (public speaking), chess club, and the U.S.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Army Junior Reserve Officers' Training Corps (JROTC) program where he reached its highest rank—cadet colonel.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson served as a laboratory assistant in the high school's biology, chemistry, and physics school laboratories beginning in grades 10, 11, and 12, respectively, and worked as a biology laboratory assistant at Wayne State University the summer between grades 11 and 12.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In his book *Gifted Hands*, Carson relates that as a youth, he had a violent temper.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] "As a teenager, I would go after people with rocks, and bricks, and baseball bats, and hammers", Carson told NBC's *Meet the Press* in October 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He said he once tried to hit his mother on the head with a hammer over a clothing dispute, while in the ninth grade he tried to stab a friend who had changed the radio station.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Fortunately, the blade broke in his friend's belt buckle.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson said the intended victim, whose identity he wants to protect, was a classmate, a friend, or a close relative.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] After this incident, Carson said he began reading the Book of Proverbs and applying verses on anger.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] As a result, he states he "never had another problem with temper".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In his various books and at campaign events, he repeated these stories and said he once attacked a schoolmate with a combination lock.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Nine friends, classmates, and neighbors who grew up with him told CNN in 2015 they did not remember the anger or violence he has described.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In response, Carson posted on Facebook a 1997 *Parade* magazine issue, in which his mother verified the stabbing incident.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He then questioned the extent of the effort CNN had exerted in the investigation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson has said that he protected white students in a biology lab after a race riot broke out at his high school in response to the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. in 1968.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* confirmed the riot but could not find anyone who remembered Carson sheltering white students.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He wanted to attend college farther away than his brother who was at the University of Michigan.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson says he narrowed his college choices to Harvard or Yale but could only afford the $10 application fee to apply for only one of them.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He said he decided to apply to Yale after seeing a team from Yale defeat a team from Harvard on the *G.E.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was accepted by Yale and offered a full scholarship covering tuition, room and board.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1973, Carson graduated with a Bachelor of Arts degree in psychology from Yale "with a fairly respectable grade point average although far from the top of the class".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson does not say in his books whether he received a college student deferment during the Vietnam War.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He does say that his older brother, then a student at the University of Michigan, received a low number (26) in the first draft lottery in 1969 and was able to enlist in the Navy for four years instead of being drafted, whereas he received a high number (333) in the second draft lottery in 1970.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson said he would have readily accepted his responsibility to fight had he been drafted, but he "identified strongly with the anti-war protesters and the revolutionaries" and enthusiastically voted for anti-war Democratic presidential candidate George McGovern in 1972.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In his book, *America the Beautiful* (2012), Carson said, "The Vietnam War was, in retrospect, not a noble conflict.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] At Yale, Carson had a part-time job on campus as a student police aide.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In his autobiography, Carson said he had been offered a scholarship to West Point.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Cadets receive a free education and room and board in exchange for a commitment to serve in the military for at least five years after graduation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson also said the University of Michigan had offered him a scholarship.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] His staff later said the described scenario was similar to that of West Point, as he never actually applied for entry to the University of Michigan.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In his autobiography, *Gifted Hands*, Carson recounted that exams for a Yale psychology course he took his junior year, "Perceptions 301", were inexplicably burned, forcing students to retake the exam.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson said other students walked out in protest when they discovered the retest was significantly harder than the original examination, but that he alone finished the test.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On doing so, Carson said he was congratulated by the course instructor, who told him the retest was a hoax intended to find "the most honest student in the class".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson said the professor awarded him $10 and that a photographer for the *Yale Daily News* was present to take his picture, which appeared in the student newspaper with a story about the experiment.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Doubts were raised about this story in 2015 during Carson's presidential campaign.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson, while acknowledging the class number was not correct, said: "You know, when you write a book with a co-writer and you say that there was a class, a lot of [the] time they'll put a number or something just to give it more meat.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson entered the University of Michigan Medical School in 1973, and at first he struggled academically, doing so poorly on his first set of comprehensive exams that his faculty adviser recommended he drop out of medical school or take a reduced academic load and take longer to finish.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He continued with a regular academic load, and his grades improved to average in his first year of medical school.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] By his second year of medical school, Carson began to excel academically by seldom attending lectures and instead studying textbooks and lecture notes from 6 a.m. to 11 p.m.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson graduated from the University of Michigan Medical School with an M.D. degree in 1977, and he was elected to the Alpha Omega Alpha Honor Medical Society.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was then accepted by the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine neurosurgery program, where he served one year as a surgical intern and five years as a neurosurgery resident, completing the final year as chief resident in 1983.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He then spent one year (1983–1984) as a Senior Registrar in neurosurgery at the Sir Charles Gairdner Hospital in Nedlands, a suburb of Perth, Western Australia.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Upon returning to Johns Hopkins in 1984, Carson was appointed the university's director of pediatric neurosurgery.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] As a surgeon, he specialized in traumatic brain injuries, brain and spinal cord tumors, achondroplasia, neurological and congenital disorders, craniosynostosis, epilepsy, and trigeminal neuralgia.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] While at Johns Hopkins, Carson figured in the revival of the hemispherectomy, a drastic surgical procedure in which part or all of one hemisphere of the brain is removed to control severe pediatric epilepsy.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Freeman, he refined the procedure in the 1980s and performed it many times.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1987, Carson was the lead neurosurgeon of a 70-member surgical team that separated conjoined twins Patrick and Benjamin Binder, who had been joined at the back of the head (craniopagus twins).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The separation surgery held promise in part because the twin boys had separate brains.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The Johns Hopkins Children's Center surgical team rehearsed the surgery for weeks, practicing on two dolls secured together by Velcro.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Although there were few follow-up stories after the Binder twins' return to Germany seven months after the operation, both twins were reportedly "far from normal" two years after the procedure, with one in a vegetative state.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Neither twin was ever able to talk or care for himself, and both eventually became institutionalized wards of the state.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Patrick Binder died sometime between the late 2000s and early 2010s, according to his uncle, who was located by *The Washington Post* in 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The Binder surgery served as a model for similar twin separations, with its procedure being refined in subsequent decades.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson participated in four subsequent high-risk conjoined-twin separations, including a 1997 operation on craniopagus Zambian twins Joseph and Luka Banda, which resulted in a normal neurological outcome.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Two sets of twins died, including Iranian twins Ladan and Laleh Bijani.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Another separation resulted in the death of one twin and the survival of the other, who is legally blind and struggles to walk.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In September 1992, Carson appeared in an advertisement opposing Maryland Question 6, a referendum on a bill to codify the *Roe v.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Wade* decision, in which he said he opposed abortion and would refer patients seeking the procedure to other doctors.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He later condemned the advertisement and asked for it to be taken down, saying that he had not known that he was making a political advertisement and did not support making abortion illegal.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In March 2013, Carson announced he would retire as a surgeon, saying he would "much rather quit when I'm at the top of my game".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] His retirement became official on July 1, 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 2021, Carson joined Galectin Therapeutics to assist with development of the company's galectin-3 inhibitor, belapectin, as a treatment for NASH cirrhosis and in combination with immunotherapy for the treatment of cancers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson has written many articles in peer-reviewed journals and six bestselling books published by Zondervan, an international Christian media and publishing company.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The first book was an autobiography published in 1992.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Two others are about his personal philosophies of success and what he sees as the stabilizing influence of religion.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] According to CNN, Carson had an "extensive relationship" from 2004 to 2014 with Mannatech, a multi-level marketing company that produces dietary supplements made from substances such as aloe vera extract and larch-tree bark.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson gave four paid speeches at company events.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He has denied being paid by Mannatech to do anything else, saying he has been a "prolific speaker" who has addressed many groups.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In a 2004 speech, he credited the company's products with the disappearance of his prostate cancer symptoms.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The nature of this relationship became an issue in 2015 during Carson's presidential campaign.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson's relationship with Mannatech continued after the company paid $7 million in 2009 to settle a deceptive-marketing lawsuit in Texas over claims that its products could cure autism and cancer.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] His most recent paid speech for the company was in 2013, for which he was paid $42,000.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] His image appeared on the corporation's website in 2014, and in the same year, he praised their "glyconutrient" supplements in a PBS special that was subsequently featured on the site.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] During the CNBC GOP debate on October 28, 2015, Carson was asked about his relationship with Mannatech.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] I didn't have any involvement with Mannatech.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] I did speeches for other people—they were paid speeches.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] It is absolutely absurd to say I had any kind of relation with them.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] I think it is a good product." PolitiFact rated Carson's denial of any involvement as "false", pointing to his paid speeches for Mannatech and his appearances in promotional videos in which he favorably reviewed its products, despite not being "an official spokesman or sales associate".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] When the CNBC moderator commented that Carson was on Mannatech's website, Carson replied that he had not given his permission.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Earlier, he had said he was unaware of the company's legal history.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On November 3, 2015, Mannatech said on its website that for compliance with federal campaign finance regulations, the company had removed all references to Carson before he announced his bid for the presidency.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In July 2013, Carson was hired by *The Washington Times* as a weekly opinion columnist.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In October 2013, Fox News hired Carson as a contributor to provide analysis and commentary across Fox News Channel's daytime and primetime programming, a relationship that lasted until the end of 2014.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 2014, some House Republicans (who later formed the House Freedom Caucus) approached Carson about the possibility of his standing for Speaker of the House in the event that the incumbent Speaker, John Boehner, had to step down because of intraparty disunion.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson declined, citing preparations for his 2016 presidential campaign.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Ultimately, Boehner resigned in October 2015, and Paul Ryan was elected as the new Speaker.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In financial disclosure forms, Carson and his wife reported income of between $8.9 million and $27 million from January 2014 to May 3, 2015, when he announced his presidential campaign.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He resigned from Costco's board in mid-2015, after serving on it for more than 16 years.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was chairman of the Baltimore-based biotechnology company Vaccinogen from August 2014 until the announcement of his US presidential bid in May 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson had previously served on Vaccinogen's Medical Advisory Board.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson serves on the board of Sinclair Broadcast Group.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson, who had been registered as a Republican, changed his registration to independent in the 1990s after watching Republicans impeach President Clinton for perjury regarding an extramarital affair with Monica Lewinsky.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] "I just saw so much hypocrisy in both parties", he said.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In February 2013, Carson said he was not a member of any political party.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was the keynote speaker at the National Prayer Breakfast on February 7, 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The speech garnered Carson considerable attention because the event is normally apolitical in nature, and the speech was critical of the philosophy and policies of President Barack Obama, who was sitting 10 feet away.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] About the speech, Carson said: "I don't think it was particularly political ...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] You know, I'm a physician." Regarding the policies of President Obama, he said: "There are a number of policies that I don't believe lead to the growth of our nation and don't lead to the elevation of our nation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] I don't want to sit here and say all of his policies are bad.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson's sudden popularity among conservatives led to him being invited to the 2013 Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC) as a speaker.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He tied for seventh place in the *Washington Times*/CPAC 2013 Straw Poll with 4% of the 3,000 ballots cast.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In the 2014 CPAC straw poll, he was in third place with 9% of the vote, behind senators Ted Cruz of Texas (with 11%) and Rand Paul of Kentucky (31%).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In the presidential straw poll at the 2013 Values Voter Summit, he and Rick Santorum polled 13%, with winner Ted Cruz polling 42%, and in 2014 he polled 20% to Cruz's winning 25%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On November 4, 2014, the day of the 2014 midterms, he rejoined the Republican Party, saying it was "truly a pragmatic move" because he was considering running for president in 2016.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In January 2015, *The Weekly Standard* reported that the Draft Carson Committee had raised $13 million by the end of 2014, shortly after Carson performed well in a CNN/ORC poll of potential candidates in December 2014, coming second in two different versions.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He polled 10% to Mitt Romney's 20%, but in the same poll with Romney removed from the list, Carson polled 11% to Jeb Bush's 14%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* mentioned that the Draft Carson Committee had chairmen in all of Iowa's 99 counties, and that Carson had recently led two separate Public Policy polls for the state of Pennsylvania.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On May 2, 2015, Carson proclaimed that in two days he was going to make a major announcement on his decision on whether to enter the presidential race.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In an interview with Cincinnati station WKRC-TV on May 3, 2015, Carson accidentally confirmed his candidacy for president.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The interview was also broadcast live on WPEC.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The next day, May 4, 2015, at the Music Hall Center for the Performing Arts in his home town of Detroit, he officially announced his run for the Republican nomination in the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The announcement speech was preceded by a choir singing "Lose Yourself" with Carson sitting in the audience.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In October 2015, the Super PAC supporting Carson, The 2016 Committee (formerly the Draft Carson Committee), announced it had received donations in mostly $100 increments from more than 200 small businesses around the country over the course of one week.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Fox Business reported that "Carson's outsider status is growing his small business support base." Ben Walters, a fundraiser for The 2016 Committee, expressed optimism about Carson's small business support base: "It's unbelievable the diversity of businesses that we are bringing on.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In October, it was noted that Carson's "improbable" political career had surged in polls and fundraising, while he continued to participate in nationally televised Republican debates.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The campaign brought considerable attention to Carson's past.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] CBS News described his narrative of "overcoming impossible odds as a child growing up in an impoverished, single-parent household to reach international prominence as a pediatric neurosurgeon" as "a key part of his presidential campaign".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* said his background came under "the harsh scrutiny of presidential politics, where rivals and media hunt for embellishments and omissions that can hobble a campaign".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] CNN characterized the core narrative as being "acts of violence as an angry young man", followed by a spiritual epiphany which transformed Carson into the "composed figure" he now portrays.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Media challenges to a number of Carson's statements included allegations of discrepancies between documented facts and certain assertions in his autobiography *Gifted Hands*—allegations dismissed by Carson as a media "witch hunt".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In November 2015, the *Detroit Free Press* republished an article from 1988 "to try to bring some clarity to the claims currently being brought into question".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In November 2015, Carson's campaign aired a 60-second TV advertisement in which excerpts from Carson's stump speech were intercut with a rap by an artist named Aspiring Mogul.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] They spent $150,000 on the ads, which were aired in Atlanta, Detroit, and Miami.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson defended the ad, saying, "Well, there are people in the campaign who felt that was a good way to do things...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] I support them in doing that, but I probably would have taken a little different approach." Later, he said the advertisement was done without his knowledge, that "it was done by people who have no concept of the black community and what they were doing", and that he was "horrified" by it.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In a November 2015 Republican debate, Carson declared his intentions to make ISIS "look like losers" as he would "destroy their caliphate".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson also advocated capturing a "big energy field" outside of Anbar, Iraq, which he said could be accomplished "fairly easily".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Regarding the Middle East, he also claimed that "the Chinese are there".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson said he is not opposed to a Palestinian state, but he questioned why it needs "to be within the confines of Israeli territory...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On March 2, after the Super Tuesday 2016 primaries, Carson announced that he did "not see a political path forward" and would not attend the next Republican debate in Detroit.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He said, "[T]his grassroots movement on behalf of 'We the People' will continue", indicating that he would give more details later in the week.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He suspended his campaign on March 4 and announced he would be the new honorary national chairman of My Faith Votes, a group that encourages Christians to exercise their civic duty to vote.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In total, Ben Carson's campaign spent $58 million.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] However, most of the money went to political consultants and fundraising rather than advertising.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson questioned whether his campaign was economically sabotaged from within.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On March 11, 2016, a week after Carson ended his presidential campaign, he endorsed Trump, calling him part of "the voice of the people to be heard".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson's subsequent comments that Americans would have to sustain Trump for only four years if he was not a good president drew criticism, and he admitted that he would have preferred another candidate, though he thought Trump had the best chance of winning the general election.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On the other hand, at the press conference Carson said Trump had a "cerebral" side.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On April 25, Carson expressed opposition to Harriet Tubman replacing Andrew Jackson on the $20 bill the day after dubbing the replacement "political expediency", though he indicated interest in Tubman having another tribute.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In late April, Carson wrote to the Nevada Republican Party, requesting the two delegates he won in Nevada be released and free to support whoever they want.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On May 4, after Trump wrapped up the Republican nomination, he hinted that Carson would be among those who would vet his vice-presidential pick.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The same day, in an interview Carson expressed interest in Ted Cruz serving as Attorney General of the United States, a position that Carson said would allow Cruz to prosecute Hillary Clinton, and then as a Supreme Court Justice nominee from the Trump administration.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On May 6, Carson said in an interview that Trump would consider a Democrat as his running mate, conflicting with Trump's assertion that he would not.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] A Carson spokesperson later said Carson expected Trump to select a Republican.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was said by aide Armstrong Williams in a May 10 interview to have withdrawn from the Trump campaign's vetting team, though the campaign confirmed he was still involved.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Later that month, Carson revealed a list of potential vice-presidential candidates in an interview with *The Washington Post*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On May 16, Carson said the media could not keep opinion out of reporting and cited Walter Cronkite as a fair journalist who was, in his words, a "left-wing radical".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] During the Republican National Convention, Carson appeared with former New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani in support of the pro-Donald Trump Great America PAC at an event in Cleveland.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In total, Carson received 857,039 votes during the Republican primaries; this total represented 2.75% of the votes cast.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The only jurisdiction he carried in the primaries was in the Alaska caucuses in which he won a single state house district, but this did not result in any delegates for his campaign from Alaska since the required threshold of votes statewide was not met.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He received the support of seven delegates at the Republican National Convention in Cleveland.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Trump received the Republican nomination and went on to be elected president on November 8, 2016.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] After Donald Trump's win in the 2016 election, Carson joined Trump's transition team as vice chairman.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was also offered a cabinet position in the administration.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was never offered a specific position, but everything was open to him." He was eventually offered the position of Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, which he accepted.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On December 5, 2016, President Trump announced that he would nominate Carson to the position of Secretary of Housing and Urban Development.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] During the confirmation process, Carson was scrutinized by some housing advocates for what they perceived as his lack of relevant experience.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On January 24, 2017, the Senate Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs voted unanimously to approve the nomination.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Senate Democrats attempted to defeat Carson's nomination via filibuster, but that vote failed on March 1, 2017, and he was then confirmed by the Senate by a 58–41 vote the next day.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In December 2017, *The Economist* described the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD), led by Ben Carson, as "directionless".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Most of the top HUD positions were unfilled and Carson's leadership was "inconspicuous and inscrutable".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] HUD saw an exodus of career officials during Carson's tenure.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On March 6, his first day as secretary, while addressing Housing and Urban Development (HUD) employees, Carson saluted the work ethic of immigrants, and during his comments, he likened slaves to involuntary immigrants.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] A HUD spokesman said that no one present thought Carson "was equating voluntary immigration with involuntary servitude".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In the same speech, Carson was criticized by some for saying that the human brain "was incapable of forgetting and could be electrically stimulated into perfect recall".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Under the federal budget proposed by President Trump in 2017, HUD's budget for the fiscal year 2018 would be cut by $6.2 billion (13%) and the Community Development Block Grant, a program which Carson praised in a trip to Detroit as HUD secretary, would be eliminated.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson issued a statement supporting the proposed cuts.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson suggested that federal funds for housing in Detroit could be part of an expected infrastructure bill.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In April 2017, while speaking in Washington at the National Low Income Housing Coalition conference, Carson said that housing funding would be included in an upcoming infrastructure bill from the Trump administration.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In summer 2017, Carson allowed his son, Baltimore businessman, Ben Carson Jr., to participate in organizing a HUD "listening tour" in Baltimore.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The son's involvement prompted HUD staff to express concern; the department's deputy general counsel for operations wrote in a memorandum "that this gave the appearance that the Secretary may be using his position for his son's private gain".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson's wife, son, and daughter-in-law also attended official meetings.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In February 2018, the HUD inspector general's office confirmed that it was looking into the role Carson's family played at the department.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] During congressional testimony in May 2019, while being questioned by U.S.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Representative Katie Porter, Carson did not know what the term REO ("real estate owned" refers to housing owned by a bank or lending institution post-foreclosure) stood for and confused it with the cookie, Oreo.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In response, Carson went on the Fox Business Network where he accused Democrats of adhering to "Saul Alinsky" tactics.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On March 1, 2020, the office of Vice President Mike Pence announced Carson's addition to the White House Coronavirus Task Force.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On November 9, 2020, Carson tested positive for COVID-19 after attending President Trump's Election Night party.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He initially treated himself with a homeopathic oleander extract on the recommendation of Mike Lindell, the founder of My Pillow, Inc., which Carson said caused his symptoms to disappear.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Oleander was previously rejected by the Food and Drug Administration as a treatment for COVID-19 and Carson received criticism for promoting an unscientific homeopathic treatment.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He disclosed on November 20 that he subsequently became "extremely sick" and attributed his recovery to Regeneron's experimental antibody therapy.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He said that President Trump had given him access to the drug.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson received criticism for spending up to $31,000 on a dining set in his office in late 2017.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] This expenditure was discovered after Helen Foster, a career HUD official, filed a complaint alleging that she had been demoted from her position because she refused to spend more than the legal $5,000 limit for office redecorations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson and his spokesman said that he had little or no involvement in the purchase of the dining set.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Later, email communications revealed that Carson and his wife selected the dining set.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On March 20, 2018, Carson testified before the United States House Committee on Appropriations that he had "dismissed" himself from the decision to buy the $31,000 dining room set and "left it to my wife, you know, to choose something".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On September 12, 2019, HUD's inspector general released a report clearing Carson of misconduct.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson was accused by members of the Department of Housing and Urban Development of making transphobic remarks at a meeting in San Francisco in September 2019.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He warned that "big, hairy men" might infiltrate homeless shelters for women, prompting one woman to walk out.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Joe Kennedy III of Massachusetts and Jennifer Wexton of Virginia called for his resignation, but Carson said the accusations were a "mischaracterization".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1994, Carson and his wife started the Carson Scholars Fund which awards scholarships to students in grades 4–11 for "academic excellence and humanitarian qualities".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Recipients of the Carson Scholars Fund receive a $1,000 scholarship towards their college education.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In recognition for his work with the Carson Scholars Fund and other charitable giving throughout his lifetime, Carson was awarded the William E.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Simon Prize for Philanthropic Leadership in 2005.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] On September 24, 2025, Carson was sworn in as the National Advisor for Nutrition, Health, and Housing at the U.S.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson and his wife, fellow Detroit native Lacena "Candy" Rustin, met in 1971 as students at Yale and married in 1975.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] They moved to West Friendship, Maryland, in 1988.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] They have three sons and several grandchildren.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Their oldest son was born in Perth, Australia, while Ben Carson was working at the city hospital for a year.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 2001, Ben and Candy Carson bought a 48-acre property in Upperco, Maryland.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] After being diagnosed with prostate cancer, Ben underwent a two-hour operation at Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore on August 7, 2002.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 2013, Ben, Candy, and Ben Carson's mother moved to West Palm Beach, Florida.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] While being confirmed as Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, Ben Carson bought a $1.22 million house in Vienna, Virginia, in February 2017 and sold his West Palm Beach home for over $900,000 in May 2017, after buying a $4.4 million house in nearby Palm Beach Gardens.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson and his wife are members of the Seventh-day Adventist Church (SDA).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He was baptized at Burns Seventh-day Adventist Church in Detroit.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] A few years later, he told the pastor at a church he was attending in Inkster, Michigan, that he had not fully understood his first baptism and wanted to be baptized again.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He has served as a local elder and Sabbath School teacher in the Seventh-day Adventist Church and is a member of Spencerville Seventh-day Adventist Church in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Although he is an Adventist, the church has officially cautioned church employees to remain politically neutral.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In keeping with his Seventh-day Adventist faith, Ben Carson announced in 2014 that he believed "that the United States will play a big role" in the coming apocalypse.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He said, "I hope by that time I'm not around anymore." Carson claims that he does not believe in hell as understood by some Christians: "You know, I see God as a very loving individual.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] And why would he torment somebody forever who only had a life of 60 or 70 or 80 years?
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Even if they were only evil for 80 years?" This is in line with Adventist teaching, which promotes annihilationism, the belief that souls in hell are destroyed rather than tormented.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Carson endorsed Seventh-day Adventist theology, which includes believing in a literal reading of the first chapters of Genesis.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In a 2013 interview with *Adventist News Network*, Carson said: "You know, I'm proud of the fact that I believe what God has said, and I've said many times that I'll defend it before anyone.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] If they want to criticize the fact that I believe in a literal, six-day creation, let's have at it because I will poke all kinds of holes in what they believe." Carson's Adventism was criticized by his then-primary rival Donald Trump.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Some Adventists argue that Carson's political positions on gun rights and religious liberty conflict with historic Adventist teachings in favor of nonviolence, pacifism, and the separation of church and state.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In 1998, Carson gave the commencement address at Andrews University in Berrien Springs, Michigan, the flagship institution of the Seventh Day Adventist school system.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] During the speech, Carson voiced sympathies for a long discredited belief that the pyramids of Giza were built by the Biblical figure Joseph to store grain.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] When questioned about it again in 2015, Carson stood by the assertion.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In May 2025 Donald Trump appointed Carson to be Vice Chair of the Religious Liberty Commission.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] The commission was created to advise on religious liberty policies, identify threats to freedom, and recommend protections for religious expression.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Consistent with the practice of many Adventists, Carson was a part-time lacto-ovo vegetarian (he ate dishes containing milk, eggs, or cheese and occasionally poultry).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] He said his main reason for becoming vegetarian was health concerns, including avoiding parasites and heart disease, and he emphasizes the environmental benefits of vegetarianism.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] His transition was made easier because he had eaten little meat for ascetic reasons as a child, and he readily adopted his wife's vegetarianism because she does much of the cooking in their household.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] Speaking in 1990, he said that with the increasing availability of meat substitutes, "It might take 20 years.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] But eventually there will no longer be a reason for most people to eat meat.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] And animals will breathe a sigh of relief." To avoid causing others discomfort, he is willing to occasionally eat chicken or turkey, although he finds eating pork highly unpleasant.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p01] In August 2015, Carson said he does "occasionally enjoy a nice steak or a hamburger" and does not "have anything against meat" at a town hall meeting in Iowa.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p02] Carson is a member of the American Academy of Achievement, Alpha Omega Alpha Honor Medical Society, and the Horatio Alger Association of Distinguished Americans.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p02] Carson has been awarded 38 honorary doctorate degrees and dozens of national merit citations.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p02] He is an emeritus fellow of the Yale Corporation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p02] Benjamin Carson High School of Science and Medicine for students interested in pursuing healthcare careers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-p02] The school is partnering with Detroit Receiving Hospital and Michigan State University.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] The 2016 presidential campaign of Ben Carson, a pediatric neurosurgeon and bestselling author, was announced May 3, 2015, in an interview with a local television station in Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] He formally announced his candidacy for the Republican nomination in the 2016 presidential election at a rally in his hometown of Detroit on May 4, 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] On March 4, 2016, Carson officially ended his campaign in a speech at CPAC.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] After Trump won the general election, he selected Carson to be his Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, with Carson announcing an additional administration role overseeing the repeal and replacement of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Carson entered the political scene at the 2013 National Prayer Breakfast on February 7.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In his speech, he commented on political correctness ("dangerous", because it goes against freedom of expression), education, health care, and taxation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Regarding education, he spoke favorably about graduation rates in 1831, when Alexis de Tocqueville visited the United States, and when "anybody finishing the second grade was completely literate".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] He espoused the idea of a tax-exempt health savings account created at birth, that can be bequeathed at death, along with an electronic medical record and birth certificate.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] He supports a flat tax, which he calls the "proportional tax" in reference to the biblical tithe.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] The speech garnered Carson considerable attention because the event is normally apolitical in nature, and the speech was critical of the philosophy and policies of President Barack Obama, who was sitting less than 10 feet away.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Conservative commentators from Rush Limbaugh to Sean Hannity and Neil Cavuto of Fox News praised the speech as an example of speaking "truth to power".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Carson was a featured speaker at the 2013 Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC), and tied for seventh place in the *Washington Times*/CPAC 2013 Straw Poll with 4% of the 3,000 ballots cast.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In the 2014 CPAC straw poll, he came in third place with 9% of the vote, behind senators Ted Cruz of Texas (with 11%) and Rand Paul of Kentucky (31%).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In the 2015 CPAC poll, Carson came in fourth behind Paul, Wisconsin governor Scott Walker, and Cruz with 11.4%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Carson also had a strong showing in the polls at the 2013 and 2014 Values Voter Summits; in 2013, he tied with former Pennsylvania senator Rick Santorum for second place with 13%, behind Ted Cruz's 42%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In 2014, he came in second with 20%, behind Cruz's 25%, and also came in first place in the same group's vice presidential poll.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In February 2014 a *Baltimore Sun* poll ranked him first among potential Republican candidates, with 24% (Jeb Bush was in second place with 15%); in another during the same month, an online poll of 62,000 conservative activists, Carson came in third.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In an interview with *The Weekly Standard* in May 2014, Carson said that he was "warming up to the idea" of a presidential run.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In June 2014, Carson appeared in the first national poll for the 2016 presidential election through Rasmussen.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In a hypothetical race against Hillary Clinton, Carson tied with Rand Paul for the strongest showing out of any potential Republican nominee, trailing Clinton by only 7%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Carson also polled well in a Cygnal poll in Alabama, where he came in second behind Jeb Bush.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] A group using the catchphrase "Run, Ben, Run" got started to draft him for the Republican nomination.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] The organization, then called the "National Draft Ben Carson for President Committee" and later known as "The 2016 Committee", was founded by John Philip Sousa IV, a great-grandson of John Philip Sousa.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] It has also served as the primary fundraiser for a potential campaign, with Sousa reporting on April 12 that the movement had raised over US$4 million, and that a potential campaign apparatus, from television ads to mailing lists, had already been set up.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] At the end of June 2014, the Draft Committee reported that it had raised over US$7 million from 91,000 donors.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] On August 2, 2014, it was reported that Carson had officially approved the formation of his own Political Action Committee, named One Nation, and also appointed Texas businessman Terry Giles as chairman of a potential presidential campaign.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Carson suggested that his final decision on whether or not to run would depend on the results of the 2014 midterms, and whether the Republicans would regain control of the U.S.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] This announcement came shortly after Sousa reported that the draft committee had raised yet another US$1 million, resulting in US$8 million raised overall.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] When interviewed by radio host Hugh Hewitt in late September 2014, Carson said "the likelihood is strong" that he would run for president.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] He came in second place in a similar Fox News poll, behind former Arkansas governor Mike Huckabee by 1%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] In early November 2014, following the Republicans' recapture of the Senate, Carson announced that he would air an hour-long ad called *A Breath of Fresh Air: A New Prescription for America* to introduce himself in 22 states.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] This move, along with Carson's announcement that he was officially switching his political affiliation from independent to Republican, spurred even more speculation that he would run for the Republican nomination.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] On November 7, Fox News and Carson confirmed that his relationship with the cable news channel had ended.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Carson had been hired by Fox News in October 2013.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* mentioned that the Draft Carson Committee had chairmen in all of Iowa's 99 counties, and that Carson had recently come in first place in two separate Public Policy polls for the state of Pennsylvania.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] The National Draft Ben Carson for President Committee helped make the retired neurosurgeon the first candidate successfully drafted for president since 1964, when Arizona Senator Barry Goldwater, an early leader of conservatism in the United States, won the GOP nomination.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p01] Many considered the fact that Carson has never held public office to be one of his largest obstacles, as only one person, Wendell Willkie, has ever been nominated by a major party without having held public office or flag rank in the armed forces.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On May 2, 2015, Carson proclaimed that in two days, he was going to make a major announcement on his decision on whether to enter the presidential race.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In an interview with a Cincinnati TV station WKRC (AM) on May 3, 2015, Carson accidentally confirmed his candidacy for president.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In late March 2015, Carson had his first-ever victory in a national poll for the 2016 GOP field when a Fox News poll showed him tied for first place with former Florida governor Jeb Bush (each candidate polled at 13%).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He continued to poll well in Fox News polls, later matching this same result in early May.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He also tied for first in a Quinnipiac University poll along with four others, all at 10% each; the others were Bush, Mike Huckabee, Marco Rubio, and Scott Walker.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In an early June poll by *The Economist* and YouGov, Carson tied once more with Rubio for first, at 10% each.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] His first ever first-place performance in a national poll came in mid-June, in a Monmouth University poll that had him at 11%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In late May, Carson won the presidential straw poll at the 2015 Southern Republican Leadership Conference, with 25.4% of the vote, and in July he came first in a straw poll of the Washington, D.C.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson also came in first in two consecutive annual polls from the Western Conservative Summit; in 2014, he won 22% of the vote, and in 2015, he won with 26% – 224 votes out of 871 total.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In June, a few of the most important officials in Carson's campaign, including his campaign chairman and finance chief and chief legal counsel, left; his super-PACs have been competing against each other and his own campaign fund for funding.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] An attempt is underway by his departing campaign chairperson, who must first observe a legally-mandated 120-day 'cool-off period', to form a single super-PAC (political action committee) to better channel funds.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In early July, communications director Doug Watts reported that the campaign had raised US$8.3 million over the second quarter of 2015 alone, via 210,000 donations from 151,000 donors.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Later that same month, the *Des Moines Register* reported that Carson had raised more money in Iowa than any other Republican candidate, and in the overall general election field, was rivaled in Iowa fundraising only by Democratic frontrunner Hillary Clinton.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In September 2015, Carson came in second in the Values Voter Summit presidential straw poll for the third consecutive year, once again only behind Ted Cruz, receiving 18% of the vote.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson successfully qualified for the first presidential debate of the 2016 cycle, hosted by Fox News, coming in 5th place in the overall list of the top 10 candidates.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson's performance in the first debate was well-received overall, and in a Suffolk University poll held afterward, Carson was the second-highest performing candidate in the question of who won the debate, with 22%; only Florida Senator Marco Rubio polled higher, by a margin of only 1%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] A Fox News poll released after the debate showed that Carson had the biggest average increase in poll performance and approval ratings after the debate; his average increase in most national polls was 5%, or a 71% overall increase in his position.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson quickly began to rise in many national polls, eventually polling in double digits and securing second place, only behind Trump.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson subsequently saw a significant increase in two major aggregate polls for the Republican nomination, from Real Clear Politics and *The Huffington Post* - in both cases, he rose to the #3 spot in the race for the nomination, behind Jeb Bush and Donald Trump, by mid-August.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] By late August, he had increased his lead in said aggregate polls even further to rise to the #2 position, only behind Trump.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] His rise had further fueled the perception that candidates with little to no political experience, like Carson and Trump, were the new favorite types of candidates among potential primary voters.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson's performance in the second debate was also very well-received, and solidified his status as the second highest-polling candidate.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Over the course of the three-hour debate and the hours immediately after, Carson's Facebook page gained an additional 500,000 likes.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Less than 10 days after the debate, Carson's Facebook page reached 4 million likes, thus garnering the highest amount of Facebook likes out of any candidate in the 2016 election, from either party.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson's surge after the debates also translated well into his national poll standing in general election match-ups.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Eventually, these leads resulted in Carson becoming the one and only Republican candidate who developed a lead over Hillary Clinton in both major aggregate polls, from the *Huffington Post* and Real Clear Politics.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On September 30, it was reported that Carson's campaign had raised US$20.2 million in the third quarter of 2015, thus bringing the campaign's grand total to US$31 million.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson also had the second-highest amount of money on hand at the end of the third quarter, with US$12 million, only behind Ted Cruz's US$13.5 million.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In the same period, The 2016 Committee reported that it had raised US$2.8 million and had reached a new total of 31,000 volunteers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] As the fall of 2015 began, Carson's rise in the polls began to enter the low 20s and solidified Carson as the #2 candidate by double-digit leads over the remaining candidates, while narrowing down the gap between Carson and Trump.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] This was marked by an NBC News and *The Wall Street Journal* poll where Carson garnered 20% of the vote to Trump's 21%, a Fox News poll where Carson had 23% to Trump's 24%, and eventually taking the lead himself in an IBD/TIPP poll, with 24% to Trump's 17%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] With the latter poll, Carson became the first Republican candidate in over two months to take first place over Trump in any national poll, since Jeb Bush in late July.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] An op-ed article released in conjunction with the Fox News poll declared that Carson was "giving Trump a run for his money" in the race for the nomination.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] By mid-October, Carson had increased his standing in national general election polls, with his leads over Hillary Clinton increasing to 3.5% in the Real Clear Politics poll, and 5.6% in the *Huffington Post* poll.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On October 14, it was reported that Carson was temporarily halting his presidential campaign in order to do a two-week promotional tour for his latest book, *A More Perfect Union*.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] However, Carson stated that it was not a suspension of his campaign, and he would still be holding private fundraising events throughout the two-week period.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] During the two-week period, Carson joined with frontrunner Donald Trump in threatening a boycott of CNBC over conditions for the third debate, which would be held at the end of Carson's book tour.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On October 16, CNBC announced that it had accepted the demands of Carson and Trump, setting the two-hour maximum and allowing for opening and closing statements.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] As the fall continued, Carson began to increase his lead in numerous statewide polls.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In addition to coming in second, behind Trump, in many crucial primary states, Carson took the lead himself in both Utah and Louisiana, and tied for first with Trump in Michigan, Pennsylvania, and the crucial state of Florida.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Most prominently, Carson took the lead in two consecutive Iowa polls in late October, thus becoming the first candidate to take the lead in the state since Trump took the lead from Scott Walker in mid-July.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Both immediately before and immediately after the third debate, Carson began to match Trump for first place in several nationally recognized polls.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Prior to the third debate, Carson came in first in a CBS News/*The New York Times* poll with 26% to Trump's 22%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] After the debate, he came in first in two consecutive NBC polls; in a joint poll between NBC and *The Wall Street Journal*, Carson had 29% to Trump's 23%, and in another joint poll between NBC and SurveyMonkey, both men tied at 26% each.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] With these poll numbers, Carson closed the gap with Trump in most aggregate polls, and even became the first candidate since Trump's rise to claim first place in both the Real Clear Politics and "270 to Win" aggregate polls, in early November.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson also further expanded his polling in individual states, taking the lead in Oklahoma and tying for first, with Trump, in Texas.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Lastly, Carson came in a narrow second behind Trump in a statewide poll in the early state of New Hampshire, but was well within the poll's margin of error and thus statistically tied with Trump, thus eclipsing Trump in both of the first two primary states.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] With his rise in the polls and a subsequent rise in focus, as well as numerous threats against his campaign, Carson, along with Trump, was approved to receive Secret Service protection on November 5.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] This made both Carson and Trump two of the earliest instances of presidential candidates receiving Secret Service protection in American history, over a year before the general election.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Throughout late October and early November, Carson began to face increased media scrutiny over his biographical narrative and repeatedly pushed back against most criticisms.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson continued to increase his leads in statewide polls, matching Trump for first in Arizona, Georgia, Virginia, and Maryland, while also taking the lead in North Carolina and the significant state of Colorado.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In a final showing before his national numbers dropped out of the double digits, Carson tied for first (alongside Trump) in statewide polls in Tennessee and California.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] They spent $150,000 on the ads, which were aired in Atlanta, Detroit and Miami.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson initially weakly defended the ad, saying "Well, there are people in the campaign who felt that was a good way to do things ...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] I support them in doing that, but I probably would have taken a little different approach." He then later said the advertisement was done without his knowledge, that "it was done by people who have no concept of the black community and what they were doing", and that he was "horrified" by it.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] A reporter pointed out that the advertisement contained an explicit approval statement from Carson, and he replied "Well, obviously.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] After these events and the November 2015 Paris attacks, Carson started slipping in the polls, falling 10 points in Iowa, amid scrutiny of his lack of credentials on foreign affairs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Towards the end of November, Carson made an overseas trip to visit the Azraq refugee camp in Jordan, which was housing refugees of the Syrian Civil War, as part of trying to bolster his foreign policy expertise.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Upon returning he stated that rather than refugees coming to the United States, as was being debated, they should be sheltered in nearby countries in the Middle East.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In early December, the 2015 San Bernardino attack added to the focus of national security issues in the campaign.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] By mid-December, Carson's poll numbers had fallen dramatically, both nationwide and in Iowa, where he was polling strongly.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] A national Quinnipiac poll showed Carson's support dropping from 23 to 16%, while a CBS poll showed Carson's plummeting from 26 to 13%, and an NBC/Wall Street Journal poll showed an even more dramatic decrease, from 29 to 11%.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In the Real Clear Politics average of national polls, Carson's position had fallen from first with 24.8% on November 5 to fourth with just 13.2%, behind Trump, Rubio, and Cruz, as of December 13.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In Iowa, Carson's support had fallen from 28 to 13% according to a Monmouth University poll, and from 32 to 13% in a Des Moines Register/Bloomberg poll.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] His polling average, which had previously reached 29.3% by late October, had fallen to 13.0% by mid-December.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Three of Carson's top campaign advisers, campaign manager Barry Bennett, communications director Doug Watts and deputy campaign manager Lisa Coen, resigned from the campaign in late December 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Robert Dees as his new campaign chairman and Ed Brookover as the new campaign manager.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In January 2016, Carson lost Sam Pimm, executive director of the pro-Carson super PAC the 2016 Committee, along with all of the PAC's staff in New Hampshire, when they resigned their positions and endorsed GOP rival Ted Cruz.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On January 19, a campaign volunteer, Braden Joplin, 25, was killed and three others injured in a car accident on Interstate 80 near Atlantic, Iowa.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In the Iowa Caucuses on February 1, Carson came in 4th place with 9% of the vote (over 17,000 popular votes), thus earning 3 delegates.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] However, a significant controversy arose when CNN said that Carson was taking a break from the campaign trail.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Members of Ted Cruz's campaign caught wind of the story, and began telling voters at the caucuses that Carson had dropped out.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson accused Cruz's campaign of doing this explicitly to switch potential Carson voters to Cruz, an accusation that front runner Donald Trump also began to use against Cruz.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson leveled these accusations at Cruz consistently over the next few days, particularly during the 8th GOP debate in New Hampshire on February 6.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson suffered a poor showing at the New Hampshire primary, polling at 2.3%, and receiving 0 delegates.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] During the debate on February 6, he apparently missed his introduction from the moderator, and could be seen waiting apprehensively offstage while other candidates passed by.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On March 2, following the Super Tuesday primaries, Carson announced that he did "not see a political path forward" and would not attend the next Republican debate in Detroit.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He said, however, that "this grassroots movement on behalf of 'We the People' will continue", stating that he would give more details March 4.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On March 4, Carson officially ended his campaign in a speech at CPAC.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He received the support of seven delegates at the Republican National Convention.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson has described himself as pro-life, comparing women who have abortions to historical slave owners, and supports overturning the 1973 Supreme Court decision in *Roe v.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He opposes access to abortion in virtually all cases, including pregnancies resulting from incest or rape, but would consider allowing its use if a woman's health is in danger.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson defended his past use of tissue from aborted fetuses for medical research in part, by stating, "to not use the tissue that is in a tissue bank, regardless of where it comes from, would be foolish.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson rejects the scientific consensus that human activity causes climate change; in November 2014, he said: "there's always going to be either cooling or warming going on", and he found the debate on climate change "irrelevant" and a distraction from protecting the environment.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In 2015, Carson expressed his disbelief about the scientific consensus on climate change, at a Commonwealth Club forum in San Francisco.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] After this statement, Governor Jerry Brown of California sent Carson a flash drive containing the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change's Synthesis Report, which details the scientific evidence of human impact on climate change.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson blames Washington politicians for the national debt and supports a balanced budget amendment to the United States Constitution, but has not explained how he would cut spending or raise revenue to achieve a balanced budget.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson proposed raising the minimum age to receive Social Security benefits to extend the program's solvency.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In August 2015, Carson proposed instituting a flat tax on personal and corporate income, and a capital gains tax of 10%; Carson claiming inspiration by the biblical concept of tithing.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Citizens for Tax Justice found that this plan would "raise only 32 percent of the revenue of the current tax system and pay for only 28 percent of estimated government spending" and "would increase the deficit by $3 trillion in just one year", even with every tax deduction eliminated.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson referred to progressive taxation as "socialism" in the first Republican primary debate, proposing that the U.S. abandon its current graduated personal income tax system in favor of a flat tax.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson specifically proposed a 14.9% flat tax on both personal and business income, applying to income above 150 percent of the federal poverty level.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Citizens whose income is at or below that level would be required to make an annual de minimis tax payment.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson also proposed eliminating the capital gains tax, the alternative minimum tax, and the estate tax; and individual taxes on dividends and interest.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] The plan would do away with deductions and other tax breaks.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Along with a flat tax, Carson has advocated for a national luxury tax on "very expensive" goods.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Although most of Carson's economic policy beliefs reflected "current Republican orthodoxy", he diverged from other Republican presidential candidates in his support for reinstating Glass-Steagall, a Depression-era law that separated commercial and investment banks and was repealed in 1999.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson believes the repeal of Glass-Steagall helped foster growth in banks that made them too big to fail.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson was a critic of regulations more broadly, arguing that "every single regulation costs money" and hurts consumers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] During the 2016 presidential campaign, Carson initially said the current federal minimum wage of $7.25 should "possibly" or "probably" be higher.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He supported a two-tiered minimum wage system, with a lower "starter" minimum wage for young workers.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He also supported indexing the minimum wage to inflation, "so that we never have to have this conversation again in the history of America." At a Republican primary debate in November 2015, however, Carson argued against increasing the minimum wage.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In October 2015, Carson called the size of the federal workforce "absurd" and called for reducing it by attrition.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In an October 2015 interview, Carson stated: "I actually have something I would use the Department of Education to do.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] It would be to monitor our institutions of higher education for extreme political bias and deny federal funding on that basis." This controversial suggestion was criticized by various commentators, who questioned its constitutionality and practicality.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In February 2015, at the annual Conservative Political Action Conference, Carson said: "I've found that homeschoolers do the best, private schoolers next best, charter schoolers next best, and public schoolers worst." On that basis, he advocated school choice.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson was a critic of the Common Core State Standards.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson's views on evolution and creationism have been controversial.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In a 2006 debate, Carson stated: "I don't believe in evolution ...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In a 2011 speech to Seventh-day Adventists, entitled "Celebration of Creation", Carson said Darwin's theory of evolution "was encouraged by the adversary and it has become what is scientifically, politically correct"; with "the adversary" being interpreted as a reference to Satan.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson also labeled the theory of the Big Bang as "ridiculous", saying, "Here you have all these highfalutin scientists and they're saying it was this gigantic explosion and everything came into perfect order ...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In 2014, Carson rejected the validity of carbon dating, as it "really doesn't mean anything to a God who has the ability to create anything at any point in time".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson further argued against evolution, stating his disbelief in the possibility of the "complexity of the human brain" arising "from a slime pit full of promiscuous biochemicals".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson stated in 2013 that semi-automatic firearms should be better regulated in large cities and high-crime areas.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] This statement attracted criticism from conservative opponents of gun control.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson has declined to backtrack from that view, but says he is strongly in favor of the Second Amendment, and while guns being used on innocent people was "horrible" but "not nearly as horrible as having a population that is defenseless against a group of tyrants who have arms".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson made similar remarks in October 2015.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson stated on the campaign trail also said that if he were in a position of national authority, he would allow citizens to own any weapons, including automatic and semi-automatic guns, that they could legally buy.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson has been critical of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act, saying in 2013 that "Obamacare is really I think the worst thing that has happened in this nation since slavery ...
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] And it is in a way, it is slavery in a way, because it is making all of us subservient to the government, and it was never about health care.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] It was about control." As an alternative to the Affordable Care Act, Carson said in 2013: "Here's my solution.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] When a person is born, give him a birth certificate, an electronic medical record and a health savings account." In arguing that the Affordable Care Act gave the government "control of the people", Carson several times invoked a spurious quote from Vladimir Lenin.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] As a presidential candidate, Carson supported abolishing Medicare and Medicaid, moving dollars out of these "traditional health care" programs to fund new health savings accounts.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson proposed having the government contribute $2,000 to each individual's account annually, with individuals and employers permitted to contribute additional funds to the accounts, and unspent funds being allowed to be shared within a family.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson has said that his plan "makes every family have their own insurance company." Carson estimated that his plan would cost the federal government $630 billion annually; this figure, however, does not account for population growth, inflation, or administrative costs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Separately, Carson called in a 2014 op-ed for a system "similar to Medicare and Medicaid" for a group that Carson terms the "5 percent of patients with complex pre-existing or acquired maladies." The cost of this system is not factored into Carson's $630 billion figure.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson advocated for a partially-government run plan, writing that on end-of-life care: "Decisions on who should be treated and who should not be treated would clearly require some national guidelines." In January 2015, Carson stated that his views have evolved since 1992.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In a 1998 commencement speech at Andrews University, Carson publicly expressed the view that the Pyramids of Giza were not tombs, but grain silos built by Joseph, the Biblical son of Jacob, in preparation for the famine depicted in the Book of Genesis.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He added that "various scientists" say ancient astronauts could have designed the structures, but to Carson, "it doesn't require an alien being when God is with you".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Popular in medieval Europe, the belief that Joseph had the pyramids built as granaries was perpetuated by, among others, Gregory of Tours in the sixth century, an Irish monk in the ninth century named Bernard, a mosaic in St.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Mark's Basilica dating from the twelfth, and the travelogue attributed to John Mandeville in the fourteenth.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In 2015, Carson reiterated his views on the Egyptian pyramids.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Archaeologists reject the notion that the pyramids were used to store grain, noting that the pyramids were not hollow, ancient Egyptian granaries have been well-studied, there is evidence of burials inside the pyramids, and the ancient Egyptians left funerary instructions inside them.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Additionally, the Bible states that Joseph's grain was kept in cities.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In August 2015, Carson suggesting using drones to secure the U.S.-Mexico border.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson said he did not favor "killing people" with drones, but favored using drones for surveillance and strikes to eliminate "the caves that are utilized to hide people" illegally entering the U.S. from Mexico.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In September 2015, Carson said that due to the difficulty in deporting illegal immigrants, he would instead prioritize sealing the borders of the United States, which "in the Carson administration that would be done in the first year".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He also said that "you have to also turn off the spigot that dispenses the goodies so that people don't have any incentive to come here".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In November 2015, Carson twice likened Syrian refugees to "rabid dogs" and suggested that they posed a risk to American society.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In 2014, Carson said that "I think medical use of marijuana in compassionate cases certainly has been proven to be useful" but said that he opposed legalization of recreational marijuana.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson believes marijuana is a gateway drug.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] On the legalization of recreational marijuana in Colorado, Carson said "I don't think this is something that we really want for our society.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In an appearance on Glenn Beck's show, Carson said he would "intensify" the war on drugs.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In March 2013, Carson described his views about same-sex marriage on *Hannity*, saying: "Marriage is between a man and a woman.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] No group, be they gays, be they NAMBLA, be they people who believe in bestiality, it doesn't matter what they are.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] They don't get to change the definition." The comments caused controversy.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] GLAAD criticized Carson for having "equated gays" with those from the North American Man/Boy Love Association and supporters of bestiality.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] A number of students at the Johns Hopkins School of Medicine, "enraged by Carson's comparison of homosexuality with bestiality and pedophilia", called upon Carson to withdraw as a commencement speaker.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson withdrew as speaker and apologized for his remarks, saying that he was not equating those groups.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In a 2015 Facebook post, Carson wrote that he supports civil unions for gay couples and he has "for many years".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson, while on the boards for Costco and food manufacturer Kellogg's, supported initiatives for employment non-discrimination, health insurance for domestic partners, and diversity training.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] I do not pretend to know how every individual came to their sexual orientation.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] I regret that my words to express that concept were hurtful and divisive.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In October 2014, the Southern Poverty Law Center (SPLC) added Carson to its "anti-gay extremist" list, citing Carson's "linking gays with pedophiles" and other comments; in February 2015, the SPLC removed Carson's name from its list and apologized to him.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In 2015, Carson's "main national security adviser" was Robert F.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Dees, a retired Army major general who, like Carson, argues that national security is linked to spiritual values.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Dees wrote in his book *Resilient Nations* (2014) that the greatest threat to America was not terrorism, China, or Russia but rather the decline of its "spiritual infrastructure".
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In several interviews, Carson has endorsed the views of the political theorist W.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Cleon Skousen, an author popular among Tea Party supporters, recommending Skousen's book *The Naked Communist* (1958).
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] Carson has expressed a number of often contradictory positions on the role of the United States in the Syrian Civil War.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] By September 2015, Carson had changed his position on the Assad regime, calling for forcing ISIL out of Iraq in order to allow the group to focus on overthrowing the Assad regime, whilst continuing to advocate non-intervention in Syria.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] In November 2015, Carson once again opposed U.S. assistance to Syrian rebels, instead supporting a political solution in Syria, culminating in a coalition government that would include Assad.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] He justified his new position by criticizing the United States' support for rebels in the first Libyan Civil War.
[src:azraq-refugee-camp/ben-carson-presidential-campaign-2016-p02] I would not advocate that we put a Muslim in charge of this nation.
